# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anthrax
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The **2001 anthrax attacks**, also known as **Amerithrax** (a portmanteau of "America" and "anthrax", from its FBI case name), occurred in the United States over the course of several weeks beginning on September 18, 2001, one week after the September 11 attacks.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Letters containing anthrax spores were mailed to several news media offices and to senators Tom Daschle and Patrick Leahy, killing five people and infecting seventeen others.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Capitol police officers and staffers working for Senator Russ Feingold were exposed as well.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] According to the FBI, the ensuing investigation became "one of the largest and most complex in the history of law enforcement".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] They are the only lethal attacks to have used anthrax outside of warfare.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The FBI and CDC authorized Iowa State University to destroy its anthrax archives in October 2001, which hampered the investigation.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] In the following weeks, US officials and media unsuccessfully attempted to link the attacks to Al-Qaeda and/or Ba'athist Iraq.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Thereafter, a major focus in the early years of the investigation was bioweapons expert Steven Hatfill, who was eventually exonerated.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Bruce Edwards Ivins, a scientist at the government's biodefense labs at Fort Detrick in Frederick, Maryland, became a focus around April 4, 2005.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] On April 11, 2007, Ivins was put under periodic surveillance and an FBI document stated that he was "an extremely sensitive suspect in the 2001 anthrax attacks".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] On July 29, 2008, Ivins died by suicide with an overdose of acetaminophen (paracetamol).
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Federal prosecutors declared Ivins the sole perpetrator on August 6, 2008, based on DNA evidence leading to an anthrax vial in his lab.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Two days later, Senator Chuck Grassley and Representative Rush D.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Holt Jr. called for hearings into the Department of Justice and FBI's handling of the investigation.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The FBI formally closed its investigation on February 19, 2010.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] In 2008, the FBI requested a review of the scientific methods used in their investigation from the National Academy of Sciences, which released their findings in the 2011 report *Review of the Scientific Approaches Used During the FBI's Investigation of the 2001 Anthrax Letters*.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The FBI responded by saying that the review panel asserted that it would not be possible to reach a definite conclusion based on science alone, and said that a combination of factors led the FBI to conclude that Ivins had been the perpetrator.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Some information is still sealed concerning the case and Ivins' mental health.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The government settled lawsuits that were filed by the widow of the first anthrax victim Robert Stevens for $2.5 million with no admission of liability.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The settlement was reached solely for the purpose of "avoiding the expenses and risks of further litigations", according to a statement in the agreement.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The anthrax attacks began a week after the 9/11 attacks, which had caused the destruction of the original World Trade Center in New York City, damage to the Pentagon in Arlington, Virginia, and the crash of an airliner in an empty field in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The first set of letters containing anthrax had a Trenton, New Jersey, postmark dated September 18, 2001.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Five letters are believed to have been mailed at this time to ABC News, CBS News, NBC News and the *New York Post*, all located in New York City, and to the *National Enquirer* at American Media, Inc., (AMI) in Boca Raton, Florida.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The first known victim of the attacks, Robert Stevens, who worked at the *Sun* tabloid, also published by AMI, died on October 5, 2001, four days after entering a Florida hospital with an undiagnosed illness that caused him to vomit and be short of breath.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The presumed letter containing the anthrax which killed Stevens was never found.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Only the *New York Post* and NBC News letters were actually identified; the existence of the other three letters is inferred because individuals at ABC, CBS and AMI became infected with anthrax.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Scientists examining the anthrax from the *New York Post* letter said it was a clumped coarse brown granular material which looked similar to dog food.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Two more anthrax letters, bearing the same Trenton postmark, were dated October 9, three weeks after the first mailing.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The letters were addressed to two U.S. senators, Tom Daschle of South Dakota and Patrick Leahy of Vermont.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] At the time, Daschle was the Senate majority leader and Leahy was head of the Senate Judiciary Committee; both were members of the Democratic Party.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The Daschle letter was opened by an aide, Grant Leslie, on October 15, after which the government mail service was immediately shut down.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The unopened Leahy letter was discovered in an impounded mailbag on November 16.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The Leahy letter had been misdirected to the State Department mail annex in Sterling, Virginia, because a ZIP Code was misread; a postal worker there, David Hose, contracted inhalational anthrax.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] More potent than the first anthrax letters, the material in the Senate letters was a highly refined dry powder consisting of about one gram of nearly pure spores.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] A series of conflicting news reports appeared, some claiming the powders had been "weaponized" with silicon dioxide.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Bioweapons experts who later viewed images of the anthrax used in the attacks saw no indication of "weaponization".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Tests at Sandia National Laboratories in early 2002 confirmed that the attack powders were not weaponized.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] At least 22 people developed anthrax infections, 11 of whom contracted the especially life-threatening inhalational variety.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Five died of inhalational anthrax: Stevens; two employees of the Brentwood mail facility in Washington, D.C.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Because it took so long to identify a culprit, the 2001 anthrax attacks have been compared to the Unabomber attacks which took place from 1978 to 1995.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Authorities believe that the anthrax letters were mailed from Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Investigators found anthrax spores in a city street mailbox located at 10 Nassau Street near the Princeton University campus.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] About 600 mailboxes which could have been used to mail the letters were tested for anthrax, and the Nassau Street box was the only one to test positive.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] All of the letters were copies made by a copy machine, and the originals were never found.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Each letter was trimmed to a slightly different size.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The Senate letter uses punctuation, while the media letter does not.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The handwriting on the media letter and envelopes is roughly twice the size of the handwriting on the Senate letter and envelopes.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Franklin Park, New Jersey, exists, but the ZIP Code 08852 is for nearby Monmouth Junction, New Jersey.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] There is no Greendale School in Franklin Park or Monmouth Junction, though there is a Greenbrook Elementary School in adjacent South Brunswick Township, New Jersey.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The Amerithrax investigation involved many leads which took time to evaluate and resolve.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Among them were numerous letters which initially appeared to be related to the anthrax attacks but were never directly linked.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] For example, before the New York letters were found, hoax letters mailed from St.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Petersburg, Florida, were thought to be the anthrax letters or related to them.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] A letter received at the Microsoft offices in Reno, Nevada, after the discovery of the Daschle letters, gave a false positive in a test for anthrax.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Later, because the letter had been sent from Malaysia, Marilyn W.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Thompson of *The Washington Post* connected the letter to Steven Hatfill, whose girlfriend was from Malaysia.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The letter merely contained a check and some pornography, and was neither a threat nor a hoax.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] A copycat hoax letter containing harmless white powder was opened by reporter Judith Miller in *The New York Times* newsroom.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Also unconnected to the anthrax attacks was a large envelope received at American Media, Inc., in Boca Raton, Florida (which was among the victims of the attacks), in September 2001.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] It was addressed "Please forward to Jennifer Lopez c/o The Sun", containing a metal cigar tube with a cheap cigar inside, an empty can of chewing tobacco, a small detergent carton, pink powder, a Star of David pendant, and "a handwritten letter to Jennifer Lopez.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The writer said how much he loved her and asked her to marry him." Another letter, which mimicked the original anthrax letter to Senator Daschle, was mailed to Daschle from London in November 2001, at a time when Hatfill was in England, not far from London.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Shortly before the discovery of the anthrax letters, someone sent a letter to authorities stating, "Dr.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Assaad is a potential biological terrorist." No connection to the anthrax letters was ever found.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] During the first years of the FBI's investigation, Don Foster, a professor of English at Vassar College, attempted to connect the anthrax letters and various hoax letters from the same period to Steven Hatfill.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Foster's beliefs were published in *Vanity Fair* and *Reader's Digest*.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The letters sent to the media contained a coarse brown material, while the letters sent to the two U.S.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The brown granular anthrax mostly caused cutaneous anthrax infections (9 out of 12 cases), although Kathy Nguyen's case of inhalational anthrax occurred at the same time and in the same general area as two cutaneous cases and several other exposures.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The AMI letter which caused inhalation cases in Florida appears to have been mailed at the same time as the other media letters.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The fine powder anthrax sent to Daschle and Leahy mostly caused the more dangerous form of infection known as inhalational anthrax (8 out of 10 cases).
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Postal worker Patrick O'Donnell and accountant Linda Burch contracted cutaneous anthrax from the Senate letters.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] All of the material was derived from the same bacterial strain known as the Ames strain.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The Ames strain is a common strain that was isolated from a cow in Texas in 1981.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The name "Ames" refers to the town of Ames, Iowa, but was mistakenly attached to this isolate in 1981 because of a mix-up about the mailing label on a package.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] DNA sequencing of the anthrax collected from Robert Stevens (the first victim) was conducted at The Institute for Genomic Research (TIGR) beginning in December 2001.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Sequencing was finished within a month and the analysis was published in the journal *Science* in early 2002.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Radiocarbon dating conducted by Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in June 2002 established that the anthrax was cultured no more than two years before the mailings.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Early in 2002, an FBI microbiologist noted that there were variants or mutations in the anthrax cultures grown from powder found in the letters.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Scientists at TIGR sequenced the complete genomes from 21 of these isolates during the period from 2002 to 2004.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The bioinformatics scientists at TIGR, including Steven Salzberg, Mihai Pop, and Adam M.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Phillippy, identified three relatively large changes in some of the isolates, each comprising a region of DNA that had been duplicated or triplicated.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The size of these regions ranged from 823 to 2607 base pairs, and all occurred near the same genes.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Details of these mutations were published in 2011 in the *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] These changes became the basis of polymerase chain reaction assays used to test other samples to find any that contained the same mutations.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The assays were validated over the many years of the investigation, and a repository of Ames samples was also built.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] From roughly 2003 to 2006, the repository and the screening of the 1,070 Ames samples in that repository were completed.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] On October 24, 2001, United States Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious Diseases (USAMRIID) scientist Peter Jahrling was summoned to the White House after he reported signs that silicon had been added to the anthrax recovered from the letter addressed to Daschle.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Silicon would make the anthrax more capable of penetrating the lungs.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Seven years later, Jahrling told the *Los Angeles Times* on September 17, 2008, "I believe I made an honest mistake,” adding that he had been "overly impressed" by what he thought he saw under the microscope.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Richard Preston's book *The Demon in the Freezer* provides details of conversations and events at USAMRIID during the period from October 16, 2001, to October 25, 2001.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Key scientists described to Preston what they were thinking during that period.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] When the Daschle spores first arrived at USAMRIID, the key concern was that smallpox viruses might be mixed with the spores.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] "Jahrling met [John] Ezzell in a hallway and said, in a loud voice, 'Goddamn it, John, we need to know if the powder is laced with smallpox'".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Thus, the initial search was for signs of smallpox viruses.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] On October 16, USAMRIID scientists began by examining spores that had been "in a milky white liquid" from "a field test done by the FBI's Hazardous Materials Response Unit”.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Liquid chemicals were then used to deactivate the spores.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] When scientists turned up the power on the electron beam of the Transmission Electron Microscope (TEM), "The spores began to ooze".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The anthrax terrorist or terrorists had put powdered glass, or silica, into the anthrax.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The "goop" Peter Jahrling had seen oozing from the spores was not seen when AFIP examined different spores killed with radiation.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The controversy began the day after the White House meeting.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] *The New York Times* reported, "Contradicting Some U.S.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Officials, 3 Scientists Call Anthrax Powder High-Grade – Two Experts say the anthrax was altered to produce a more deadly weapon,” and *The Washington Post* reported, "Additive Made Spores Deadlier”.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Countless news stories discussed the "additives" for the next eight years, continuing into 2010.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Later, the FBI claimed a "lone individual" could have created the anthrax spores for as little as $2,500, using readily available laboratory equipment.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] A number of press reports appeared suggesting the Senate anthrax had coatings and additives.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] *Newsweek* reported the anthrax sent to Senator Leahy had been coated with a chemical compound previously unknown to bioweapons experts.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] On October 28, 2002, *The Washington Post* reported "FBI's Theory on Anthrax is Doubted,” suggesting that the senate spores were coated with fumed silica.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Two bioweapons experts that were utilized as consultants by the FBI, Kenneth Alibek and Matthew Meselson, were shown electron micrographs of the anthrax from the Daschle letter.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] In a November 5, 2002 letter to the editors of *The Washington Post*, they stated that they saw no evidence the anthrax spores had been coated with fumed silica.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] In *Science* magazine, one group of scientists said that the material could have been made by someone knowledgeable with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Another group said it "was a diabolical advance in biological weapons technology”.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The article also specifically criticizes "a widely circulated misconception...that the spores were produced using additives and sophisticated engineering supposedly akin to military weapon production”.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The harm done by this misconception is described this way: "This idea is usually the basis for implying that the powders were inordinately dangerous compared to spores alone.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The persistent credence given to this impression fosters erroneous preconceptions, which may misguide research and preparedness efforts and generally detract from the magnitude of hazards posed by simple spore preparations".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Critics of the article complained that it did not provide supporting references.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] In late October 2001, ABC chief investigative correspondent Brian Ross linked the anthrax sample to Saddam Hussein because of its purportedly containing the unusual additive bentonite.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] On October 26, Ross said, "sources tell ABCNEWS the anthrax in the tainted letter sent to Senate Majority Leader Tom Daschle was laced with bentonite.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The potent additive is known to have been used by only one country in producing biochemical weapons—Iraq. ... [I]t is a trademark of Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein's biological weapons program ...
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The discovery of bentonite came in an urgent series of tests conducted at Fort Detrick, Maryland, and elsewhere".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] On October 28, Ross said that "despite continued White House denials, four well-placed and separate sources have told ABC News that initial tests on the anthrax by the U.S.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Army at Fort Detrick, Maryland, have detected trace amounts of the chemical additives bentonite and silica", a charge that was repeated several times on October 28 and 29.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] On October 29, 2001, White House spokesman Scott Stanzel "disputed reports that the anthrax sent to the Senate contained bentonite, an additive that ha[d] been used in Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's biological weapons program”.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Stanzel said, "Based on the test results we have, no bentonite has been found”.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The same day, Major General John Parker at a White House briefing stated, "We do know that we found silica in the samples.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Now, we don't know what that motive would be, or why it would be there, or anything.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] And that led us to be absolutely sure that there was no aluminum in the sample, because the combination of a silicate, plus aluminum, is sort of the major ingredients of bentonite".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Just over a week later, Homeland Security Advisor Tom Ridge in a White House press conference on November 7, 2001, stated, "The ingredient that we talked about before was silicon".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Neither Ross at ABC nor anyone else publicly pursued any further claims about bentonite, despite Ross's original claim that "four well-placed and separate sources" had confirmed its detection.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Some of the anthrax spores (65–75%) in the anthrax attack letters contained silicon inside their spore coats.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Silicon was even reportedly found inside the natural spore coat of a spore that was still inside the "mother germ,” which was asserted to confirm that the element was not added after the spores were formed and purified, i.e., the spores were not "weaponized”.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] In 2010, a Japanese study reported, "silicon (Si) is considered to be a "quasiessential" element for most living organisms.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] However, silicate uptake in bacteria and its physiological functions have remained obscure".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The study showed that spores from some species can contain as much as 6.3% dry weight of silicates.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] "For more than 20 years, significant levels of silicon had been reported in spores of at least some *Bacillus* species, including those of *Bacillus cereus*, a close relative of *B. anthracis*".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] According to spore expert Peter Setlow, "Since silicate accumulation in other organisms can impart structural rigidity, perhaps silicate plays such a role for spores as well".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The FBI lab concluded that 1.4% of the powder in the Leahy letter was silicon.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Scientists at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory conducted experiments in an attempt to determine if the amount of silicon in the growth medium was the controlling factor which caused silicon to accumulate inside a spore's natural coat.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The Livermore scientists tried 56 different experiments, adding increasingly high amounts of silicon to the media.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] All of their results were far below the 1.4% level of the attack anthrax, some as low as .001%.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The conclusion was that something other than the level of silicon controlled how much silicon was absorbed by the spores.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Spertzel, a microbiologist who led the United Nations' biological weapons inspections of Iraq, wrote that the anthrax used could not have come from the lab where Ivins worked.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Spertzel said he remained skeptical of the Bureau's argument despite the new evidence presented on August 18, 2008, in an unusual FBI briefing for reporters.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] He questioned the FBI's claim that the powder was less than military grade, in part because of the presence of high levels of silica.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The FBI had been unable to reproduce the attack spores with the high levels of silica.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] The FBI attributed the presence of high silica levels to "natural variability".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] This conclusion of the FBI contradicted its statements at an earlier point in the investigation, when the FBI had stated, based on the silicon content, that the anthrax was "weaponized", a step that made the powder more airy and required special scientific know-how.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] "If there is that much silicon, it had to have been added," stated Jeffrey Adamovicz, who supervised Ivins' work at Fort Detrick.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Adamovicz explained that the silicon in the anthrax attack could have been added via a large fermentor, which Battelle and some other facilities use but "we did not use a fermentor to grow anthrax at USAMRIID ... [and] We did not have the capability to add silicon compounds to anthrax spores".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Ivins had neither the skills nor the means to attach silicon to anthrax spores.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] Spertzel explained that the Fort Detrick facility did not handle anthrax in powdered form.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p01] "I don't think there's anyone there who would have the foggiest idea how to do it".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Authorities traveled to six continents, interviewed over 9,000 people, conducted 67 searches and issued over 6,000 subpoenas.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] "Hundreds of FBI personnel worked the case at the outset, struggling to discern whether the Sept.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] 11 al-Qaeda attacks and the anthrax murders were connected before eventually concluding that they were not".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The FBI and Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) both gave permission for Iowa State University to destroy the Iowa anthrax archive and the archive was destroyed on October 10 and 11, 2001.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The FBI and CDC investigation was hampered by the destruction of the large collection of anthrax spores collected over more than seven decades and kept in more than 100 vials at Iowa State University, Ames, Iowa.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Many scientists claim that the quick destruction of the anthrax spores collection in Iowa eliminated crucial evidence useful for the investigation.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] A precise match between the strain of anthrax used in the attacks and a strain in the collection would have offered hints as to when bacteria had been isolated and, perhaps, as to how widely it had been distributed to researchers.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Such genetic clues could have given investigators the evidence necessary to identify the perpetrators.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Immediately after the anthrax attacks, White House officials pressured FBI Director Robert Mueller to publicly blame al-Qaeda following the September 11 attacks.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] During the president's morning intelligence briefings, Mueller was "beaten up" for not producing proof that the killer spores were the handiwork of Osama bin Laden, according to a former aide.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] "They really wanted to blame somebody in the Middle East," the retired senior FBI official stated.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The FBI knew early on that the anthrax used was of a consistency requiring sophisticated equipment and was unlikely to have been produced in "some cave".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] At the same time, President Bush and Vice President Cheney in public statements speculated about the possibility of a link between the anthrax attacks and al-Qaeda.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] *The Guardian* reported in early October that American scientists had implicated Iraq as the source of the anthrax, and the next day *The Wall Street Journal* editorialized that al-Qaeda perpetrated the mailings, with Iraq the source of the anthrax.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Statements by the White House and public officials quickly stated that there was no bentonite in the attack anthrax.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] "No tests ever found or even suggested the presence of bentonite.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The claim was just concocted from the start.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Nonetheless, a few journalists repeated ABC's bentonite report for several years, even after the invasion of Iraq proved there was no involvement.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In an interview with Hamid Mir, Osama bin Laden denied any knowledge of the Anthrax attacks.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] On November 21, 2001, she made similar statements to the Biological and Toxic Weapons convention in Geneva.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In December 2001, she published "A Compilation of Evidence and Comments on the Source of the Mailed Anthrax" via the website of the Federation of American Scientists (FAS), claiming that the attacks were "perpetrated with the unwitting assistance of a sophisticated government program".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] She discussed the case with reporters from *The New York Times*.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In Rosenberg's assessment, the suspect(s) must have had "the right skills, experience with anthrax, up-to-date anthrax vaccination, forensic training and access to USAMRIID and its biological agents".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] On January 4, 2002, Nicholas Kristof of *The New York Times* published a column titled "Profile of a Killer" stating "I think I know who sent out the anthrax last fall".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] For months, Rosenberg gave speeches and stated her beliefs to many reporters from around the world.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] She posted "Analysis of the Anthrax Attacks" to the FAS website on January 17, 2002.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] On February 5, 2002, she published "Is the FBI Dragging Its Feet?".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In response, the FBI stated, "There is no prime suspect in this case at this time".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] *The Washington Post* reported, "FBI officials over the last week have flatly discounted Dr.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] On June 13, 2002, Rosenberg posted "The Anthrax Case: What the FBI Knows" to the FAS site.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] On June 18, 2002, she presented her theories to Senate staffers working for Senators Daschle and Leahy.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] On June 25, the FBI publicly searched Steven Hatfill's apartment, and he became a household name.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] "The FBI also pointed out that Hatfill had agreed to the search and is not considered a suspect".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The American Prospect and Salon.com reported, "Hatfill is not a suspect in the anthrax case, the FBI says".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] On August 3, 2002, Rosenberg told the media that the FBI asked her if "a team of government scientists could be trying to frame Steven J.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In August 2002, Attorney General John Ashcroft labeled Hatfill a "person of interest" in a press conference, though no charges were brought against him.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Hatfill is a virologist, and he vehemently denied that he had anything to do with the anthrax mailings and sued the FBI, the Justice Department, Ashcroft, Alberto Gonzales, and others for violating his constitutional rights and for violating the Privacy Act.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] On June 27, 2008, the Department of Justice announced that it would settle Hatfill's case for $5.8 million.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Hatfill also sued *The New York Times* and its columnist Kristof, as well as Donald Foster, *Vanity Fair*, *Reader's Digest*, and Vassar College for defamation.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The case against *The New York Times* was initially dismissed, but it was reinstated on appeal.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The dismissal was upheld by the appeals court on July 14, 2008, on the basis that Hatfill was a public figure and malice had not been proven.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The Supreme Court rejected an appeal on December 15, 2008.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Hatfill's lawsuits against *Vanity Fair* and *Reader's Digest* were settled out of court in February 2007, but no details were made public.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The statement released by Hatfill's lawyers said, "Dr.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Hatfill's lawsuit has now been resolved to the mutual satisfaction of all the parties".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Ivins had worked for 18 years at the government's bio defense labs at Fort Detrick as a biodefense researcher.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The Associated Press reported on August 1, 2008, that he had apparently committed suicide at the age of 62.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] It was widely reported that the FBI was about to press charges against him, but the evidence was largely circumstantial and the grand jury in Washington reported that it was not ready to issue an indictment.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Holt Jr. represented the district where the anthrax letters were mailed, and he said that circumstantial evidence was not enough and asked FBI director Robert S.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Mueller to appear before Congress to provide an account of the investigation.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Ivins' death left two unanswered questions.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Scientists familiar with germ warfare said that there was no evidence that he had the skills to turn anthrax into an inhalable powder.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Alan Zelicoff aided the FBI investigation, and he stated: "I don't think a vaccine specialist could do it...
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Russell Byrne worked in the bacteriology division of the Fort Detrick research facility.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] He said that Ivins was "hounded" by FBI agents who raided his home twice, and he was hospitalized for depression during that time.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] According to Byrne and local police, Ivins was removed from his workplace out of fears that he might harm himself or others.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] "I think he was just psychologically exhausted by the whole process," Byrne said.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] "There are people who you just know are ticking bombs.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] On August 6, 2008, federal prosecutors declared Ivins the sole perpetrator of the crime when US Attorney Jeffrey A.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] "The genetically unique parent material of the anthrax spores... was created and solely maintained by Dr.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] But other experts disagreed, including biological warfare and anthrax expert Meryl Nass, who stated: "Let me reiterate: no matter how good the microbial forensics may be, they can only, at best, link the anthrax to a particular strain and lab.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] They *cannot* link it to any individual".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] At least 10 scientists had regular access to the laboratory and its anthrax stock, and possibly quite a few more, counting visitors from other institutions and workers at laboratories in Ohio and New Mexico that had received anthrax samples from the flask.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The FBI later claimed to have identified 419 people at Fort Detrick and other locations who had access to the lab where flask RMR-1029 was stored, or who had received samples from flask RMR-1029.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Ivins told a mental health counselor more than a year before the anthrax attacks that he was interested in a young woman who lived out of town and that he had "mixed poison" which he took with him when he went to watch her play in a soccer match.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] "If she lost, he was going to poison her," said the counselor, who treated Ivins at a Frederick clinic four or five times in mid-2000.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] She said that Ivins emphasized that he was a skillful scientist who "knew how to do things without people finding out".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The counselor was so alarmed by his emotionless description of a specific, homicidal plan that she immediately alerted the head of her clinic and a psychiatrist who had treated Ivins, as well as the Frederick Police Department.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] She said that the police told her that nothing could be done because she did not have the woman's address or last name.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In 2008, Ivins told a different therapist that he planned to kill his co-workers and "go out in a blaze of glory".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] That therapist stated in an application for a restraining order that Ivins had a "history dating to his graduate days of homicidal threats, actions, plans, threats and actions towards therapists".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] David Irwin, his psychiatrist, called him "homicidal, sociopathic with clear intentions".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] According to the report on the Amerithrax investigation published by the Department of Justice, Ivins engaged in actions and made statements that indicated a consciousness of guilt.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] He took environmental samples in his laboratory without authorization and decontaminated areas in which he had worked without reporting his activities.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] He also threw away a book about secret codes, which described methods similar to those used in the anthrax letters.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Ivins threatened other scientists, made equivocal statements about his possible involvement in a conversation with an acquaintance, and put together outlandish theories in an effort to shift the blame for the anthrax mailings to people close to him.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The FBI said that Ivins' justifications for his actions after the environmental sampling, as well as his explanations for a subsequent sampling, contradicted his explanation for the motives for the sampling.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] According to the Department of Justice, flask RMR-1029, which was created and controlled by Ivins, was used to create "the murder weapon".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In 2002, researchers did not believe it was possible to distinguish between anthrax variants.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In January 2002, Ivins suggested that DNA sequencing should show differences in the genetics of anthrax mutations which would allow the source to be identified.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Despite researchers advising the FBI that this may not have been possible, Ivins tutored agents on how to recognize them.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Considered cutting edge at the time, the technique is now commonplace.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In February 2002, Ivins volunteered to provide samples from several variants of the Ames strain in order to compare their morphs.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] He submitted two test tube "slants" each from four samples of the Ames strain in his collection.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Two of the slants were from flask RMR-1029.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Although the slants from flask RMR-1029 were later reported to be a positive match, all eight slants were reportedly in the wrong type of test tube and would therefore not be usable as evidence in court.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] On March 29, 2002, Ivins' boss instructed Ivins and others in suites B3 and B4 on how to properly prepare slants for the FBI Repository.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The subpoena also included instructions on the proper way to prepare slants.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] When Ivins was told that his February samples did not meet FBIR requirements, he prepared eight new slants.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The two new slants prepared from flask RMR-1029 submitted in April by Ivins did not contain the mutations that were later determined to be in flask RMR-1029.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] It was reported that in April 2004, Henry Heine found a test tube in the lab containing anthrax and contacted Ivins.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In an email sent in reply, Ivins reportedly told him it was probably RMR-1029 and for Heine to forward a sample to the FBI.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Doubts regarding the reliability of the FBI tests were later raised when the FBI tested Heine's sample and a further one from Heine's test tube: one tested negative and one positive.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] A DOJ summary report of February 19, 2010, said that "the evidence suggested that Dr.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Ivins obstructed the investigation either by providing a submission which was not in compliance with the subpoena, or worse, that he deliberately submitted a false sample".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Records released under the Freedom of Information Act in 2011 show that Ivins provided four sets of samples from 2002 to 2004, twice the number the FBI reported.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Three of the four sets tested positive for the morphs.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The FBI said that "At a group therapy session on July 9, 2008, Dr.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] He revealed to the counselor and psychologist leading the group, and other members of the group, that he was a suspect in the anthrax investigation and that he was angry at the investigators, the government, and the system in general.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] He said he was not going to face the death penalty, but instead had a plan to 'take out' co-workers and other individuals who had wronged him.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] He noted that it was possible, with a plan, to commit murder and not make a mess.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] He stated that he had a bullet-proof vest, and a list of co-workers who had wronged him, and said that he was going to obtain a Glock firearm from his son within the next day, because federal agents were watching him and he could not obtain a weapon on his own.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] He added that he was going to 'go out in a blaze of glory'".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] While in a mental hospital, Ivins allegedly made menacing phone calls to his social worker Jean Duley on July 11 and 12.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In the letters sent to the media, the characters 'A' and 'T' were sometimes emboldened or highlighted by tracing over, according to the FBI suggesting that the letters contained a hidden code.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Some believe the letters to the *New York Post* and Tom Brokaw contained a "hidden message" in such highlighted characters.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] According to the FBI, Summary Report issued on February 19, 2010, following the search of Ivins' home, cars, and office on November 1, 2007, investigators began examining his trash.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The book *Gödel, Escher, Bach* contains a lengthy description of the encoding/decoding procedures, including an illustration of hiding a message within a message by emboldening certain characters.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] According to the FBI Summary Report, "[w]hen they lifted out just the bolded letters, investigators got TTT AAT TAT – an apparent hidden message".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The 3-letter groups are codons, "meaning that each sequence of three nucleic acids will code for a specific amino acid".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The FBI Summary Report proceeds to say: "From this analysis, two possible hidden meanings emerged: (1) 'FNY' – a verbal assault on New York, and (2) PAT – the nickname of [Dr.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Ivins was known to have a dislike for New York City, and four of the media letters had been sent to New York.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The report states that it "was obviously impossible for the Task Force to determine with certainty that either of these two translations was correct", however, "the key point to the investigative analysis is that there is a hidden message, not so much what that message is".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] According to the FBI, Ivins showed a fascination with codes and also had an interest in secrets and hidden messages, and was familiar with biochemical codons.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Experts have suggested that the anthrax mailings included a number of indications that the mailer was trying to avoid harming anyone with his warning letters.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The seams on the backs of the envelopes were taped over as if to make certain the powders could not escape through open seams.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The letters were folded with the "pharmaceutical fold", which was used for centuries to safely contain and transport doses of powdered medicines (and currently to safely hold trace evidence).
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The media letters provided "medical advice": "TAKE PENACILIN [*sic*] NOW".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The Senate letters informed the recipient that the powder was anthrax: "WE HAVE THIS ANTHRAX".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] At the time of the mailings, it was generally believed that such powders could not escape from a sealed envelope except through the two open corners where a letter opener is inserted, which had been taped shut.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In June 2008, Ivins was involuntarily committed to a psychiatric hospital.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The FBI stated that during a June 5 group therapy session there, Ivins had a conversation with an unnamed witness, during which he made a series of statements about the anthrax mailings that the FBI said could best be characterized as "non-denial denials".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] When asked about the anthrax attacks and whether he could have had anything to do with them, the FBI said that Ivins admitted he suffered from loss of memory, stating that he would wake up dressed and wonder if he had gone out during the night.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] After the FBI announced that Ivins acted alone, many people with a broad range of political views, some of whom were colleagues of Ivins, expressed doubts.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Reasons cited for these doubts include that Ivins was only one of 100 people who could have worked with the vial used in the attacks and that the FBI could not place him near the New Jersey mailbox from which the anthrax was mailed.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The FBI's own genetic consultant, Claire Fraser-Ligget, stated that the failure to find any anthrax spores in Ivins' house, vehicle or on any of his belongings seriously undermined the case.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Alternative theories proposed include FBI incompetence, that Syria or Iraq directed the attacks, or that similar to some 9/11 conspiracy theories the US government knew in advance that the attacks would occur.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] *The Washington Post* called for an independent investigation in the case saying that reporters and scientists were poking holes in the case.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In 2011 Leahy maintained to the *Washington Post* that the attacks had certainly involved other "people who at the very least were accessories after the fact," and also found it "strange that one person would target such an odd collection of media and political figures".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Tom Daschle, the other Democratic senator targeted, believes Ivins was the sole culprit.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Although the FBI matched the genetic origin of the attack spores to the spores in Ivins' flask RMR-1029, the spores within that flask did not have the same silicon chemical "fingerprint" as the spores in the attack letters.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The implication is that spores taken out of flask RMR-1029 had been used to grow *new* spores for the mailings.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] National Research Council, the operating arm of the National Academy of Sciences, convened a review committee that heard testimony from Henry Heine, a microbiologist who was formerly employed at the Army's biodefense laboratory in Maryland where Ivins had worked.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Heine told the panel that it was impossible that the deadly spores had been produced undetected in Ivins' laboratory, as maintained by the FBI.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] He testified that at least a year of intensive work would have been required using the equipment at the army lab to produce the quantity of spores contained in the letters and that such an intensive effort could not have escaped the attention of colleagues.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Heine also told the panel that lab technicians who worked closely with Ivins have told him they saw no such work.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] He stated further that biological containment measures where Ivins worked were inadequate to prevent Anthrax spores from floating out of the laboratory into animal cages and offices.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] "You'd have had dead animals or dead people," Heine said.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] According to Science Magazine, "Heine caveated his remarks by saying that he himself had no experience making anthrax stocks".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Science magazine provides additional comments by Adam Driks of Loyola who stated that the amount of anthrax in the letters could be made in "a number of days".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The paper is largely based on the high level of tin detected in tests of the mailed anthrax, and the tin may have been used to encapsulate the spores, which required processing not possible in laboratories to which Ivins had access.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] According to the scientific article, this raises the possibility that Ivins was not the perpetrator or did not act alone.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Earlier in the investigation, the FBI had named tin as a substance "of interest" but the final report makes no mention of it and fails to address the high tin content.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The chairwoman of the National Academy of Sciences panel that reviewed the FBI's scientific work and the director of a separate review by the Government Accountability Office said that the issues raised by the paper should be addressed.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Kiel, a retired Air Force scientist who worked on anthrax for many years, did not agree with the authors' assessments — saying that the tin might be a random contaminant rather than a clue to complex processing.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Kiel said that tin might simply be picked up by the spores as a result of the use of metal lab containers, although he had not tested that idea.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In 2011, the chief of the Bacteriology Division at the Army laboratory, Patricia Worsham, said it lacked the facilities in 2001 to make the kind of spores in the letters.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In 2011, the government conceded that the equipment required was not available in the lab, calling into question a key pillar of the FBI's case, that Ivins had produced the anthrax in his lab.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] According to Worsham, the lab's equipment for drying spores, a machine the size of a refrigerator, was not in containment so that it would be expected that non-immunized personnel in that area would have become ill.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Colleagues of Ivins at the lab have asserted that he could not have grown the quantity of anthrax used in the letters without their noticing it.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] A spokesman for the Justice Department said in 2011 that the investigators continue to believe that Ivins acted alone.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Other members of Congress have also called for an independent investigation.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In what appears to have been a response to lingering skepticism, on September 16, 2008, the FBI asked the National Academy of Sciences (NAS) to conduct an independent review of the scientific evidence that led the agency to implicate U.S.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Army researcher Bruce Ivins in the anthrax letter attacks of 2001.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] However, despite taking this action, Director Mueller said that the scientific methods applied in the investigation had already been vetted by the research community through the involvement of several dozen non-agency scientists.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The NAS review officially got underway on April 24, 2009.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In mid-2009, the NAS committee held public sessions, in which presentations were made by scientists, including scientists from the FBI laboratories.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In September 2009, scientists, including Paul Keim of Northern Arizona University, Joseph Michael of Sandia National Laboratory and Peter Weber of Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, presented their findings.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In one of the presentations, scientists reported that they did not find any silica particles on the outside of the spores (i.e., there was no "weaponization"), and that only some of the spores in the anthrax letters contained silicon inside their spore coats.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] One of the spores was still inside the "mother germ", yet it already had silicon inside its spore coat.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In October 2010, the FBI submitted materials to NAS that it had not previously provided.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Included in the new materials were results of analyses performed on environmental samples collected from an overseas site.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Those analyses yielded evidence of the Ames strain in some samples.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] NAS recommended a review of those investigations.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The NAS committee released its report on February 15, 2011, concluding that it was "impossible to reach any definitive conclusion about the origins of the anthrax in the letters, based solely on the available scientific evidence".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The report also challenged the FBI and U.S.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Justice Department's conclusion that a single-spore batch of anthrax maintained by Ivins at his laboratory at Fort Detrick in Maryland was the parent material for the spores in the anthrax letters.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] A study by the United States Government Accountability Office found shortcomings in the FBI's testing methods.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Dozens of buildings were contaminated with anthrax as a result of the mailings.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Bio Recovery provided the labor and equipment, such as HEPA filtered negative pressure air scrubbers, HEPA vacuums, respirators, cyclone foggers, and decontamination foam licensed by the Sandia National Laboratories.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Ninety-three bags of anthrax-contaminated mail were removed from the *New York Post* alone.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The decontamination of the Brentwood postal facility took 26 months and cost $130 million.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The Hamilton, New Jersey, postal facility remained closed until March 2005; its cleanup cost $65 million.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The United States Environmental Protection Agency led the collaborative effort to clean up the Hart Senate Office Building, where Senate Majority Leader Tom Daschle's office was located, as well as the Ford Office Building and several other locations around the capitol.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] It used $27 million of its funds for its Superfund program on the Capitol Hill anthrax cleanup.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] One FBI document said the total damage exceeded $1 billion.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The anthrax attacks, as well as the September 11, 2001 attacks, spurred significant increases in U.S. government funding for biological warfare research and preparedness.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] For example, biowarfare-related funding at the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID) increased by $1.5 billion in 2003.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] In 2004, Congress passed the Project Bioshield Act, which provides $5.6 billion over ten years for the purchase of new vaccines and drugs.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] These included the monoclonal antibody raxibacumab, which treats anthrax as well as an Anthrax Vaccine Adsorbed, both of which are stockpiled by the US government.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Immediately after 9/11, well before the mailing of any of the letters involved in the anthrax attacks, the White House began distributing ciprofloxacin, the only drug approved by the U.S.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Food and Drug Administration for the treatment of inhalational anthrax, to senior staffers.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Ciprofloxacin manufacturer Bayer agreed to provide the United States with 100,000 doses for $.95 per dose, a cut in the price from $1.74.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The Canadian government had previously overridden the Bayer patent, and the US was threatening the same measure if Bayer did not agree to negotiate the price.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Shortly afterward, it was recommended that doxycycline was a more appropriate drug to treat anthrax exposure.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] A widened use of the broad-spectrum antibiotic ciprofloxacin had also raised serious concerns amongst scientists about the creation and increased spread of drug-resistant bacteria strains.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Numerous corporations offered to supply drugs free of charge, contingent on the Food and Drug Administration approving their products for anthrax treatment.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] They included Bristol Myers Squibb (gatifloxacin), Johnson and Johnson (levofloxacin) and GlaxoSmithKline (two drugs).
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Eli Lilly and Pfizer also offered to provide drugs at cost.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The attack led to the widespread confiscation and curtailment of US Mail, especially to US media companies: "checks, bills, letters, and packages simply stopped arriving.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] For many people and businesses that had resisted the cultural shift to e-mail, this was the moment that pushed them online".
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] After the 9/11 attacks and the subsequent anthrax mailings, lawmakers were pressed for legislation to combat further terrorist acts.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Under heavy pressure from then Attorney General John D.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Ashcroft, a bipartisan compromise in the House Judiciary Committee allowed legislation for the Patriot Act to move forward for full consideration later that month.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] A theory that Iraq was behind the attacks, based upon purported evidence that the powder was weaponized and some reports of alleged meetings between 9/11 conspirators and Iraqi officials, may have contributed to the movement leading up to the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Years after the attack, several anthrax victims reported lingering health problems including fatigue, shortness of breath, and memory loss.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] A 2004 study proposed that the total number of people harmed by the anthrax attacks of 2001 should be raised to 68.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] A postal inspector, William Paliscak, became severely ill and disabled after removing an anthrax-contaminated air filter from the Brentwood mail facility on October 19, 2001.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Although his doctors, Tyler Cymet and Gary Kerkvliet, believe that the illness was caused by anthrax exposure, blood tests did not find anthrax bacteria or antibodies, and therefore the CDC does not recognize it as a case of inhalational anthrax.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The case was referenced on season 4, episode 24 of *Criminal Minds*.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The second season of the National Geographic TV series *The Hot Zone* focused on the attack.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Season 12, episode 13 of *Unsolved Mysteries* prominently featured the anthrax attacks in detail.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Dan Krauss's *The Anthrax Attacks: In the Shadow of 9/11* from Netflix and the BBC takes a "quasi-documentary" approach to the investigation.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Season 8, episode 3 of *How It Really Happened* covers the timeline of the attacks and investigation; it was first streamed in June 2024.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Season 1, episode 13 of *House, M.D.*, titled "Cursed", references Amerithrax.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] House diagnoses a 12-year-old child with anthrax, he jokingly mentions Saddam Hussein, although Saddam had no involvement with 9/11 or Amerithrax.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Shortly after, the patient's father, an U.S.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Air Force test pilot, sarcastically mentions terrorism.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] Season 2, episode 23 of *Law and Order: Criminal Intent* uses the events as direct inspiration.
[src:anthrax/2001-anthrax-attacks-p02] The episode involves a scientist who is falsely accused of an anthrax attack and later commits suicide because of the accusations.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was most recently revised for its ninth edition of 1940.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] Abridged versions and a supplement exist.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was initially the basis for the 2021 *Cambridge Greek Lexicon*, although subsequently that became a complete rewrite from scratch.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The lexicon was begun in the 19th century, and is now in its ninth (revised) edition, published in 1940.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was based on the earlier *Handwörterbuch der griechischen Sprache* by the German lexicographer Franz Passow (first published in 1819, fourth edition 1831), which in turn was based on Johann Gottlob Schneider's *Kritisches griechisch-deutsches Handwörterbuch*.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Lexicon* has served as the basis for all later lexicographical work on the ancient Greek language, such as the ongoing Greek–Spanish dictionary project *Diccionario Griego–Español* (DGE).
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is now conventionally referred to as *Liddell & Scott*, *Liddell–Scott–Jones*, or *LSJ*, and its three sizes are sometimes referred to as "The Little Liddell", "The Middle Liddell" and "The Big Liddell" or "The Great Scott".
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ main edition has 116,502 entries.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] According to Stuart Jones's preface to the ninth (1925) edition, the creation of the *Lexicon* was originally proposed by David Alphonso Talboys, an Oxford publisher.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was published by the Clarendon Press at Oxford rather than by Talboys, who died before the first edition (1843) was complete.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The first editor of the LSJ, Henry George Liddell, was Dean of Christ Church, Oxford, and the father of Alice Liddell, the eponymous Alice of the writings of Lewis Carroll.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The eighth edition (1897) was the last edition published during Liddell's lifetime.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ is sometimes compared and contrasted with *A Latin Dictionary* by Lewis and Short, which was also published by Oxford University Press (OUP).
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is also sometimes compared with the Bauer lexicon, which is a similar work focused on the Greek of the New Testament.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ's definitions reflect the Victorian morality of its time, using euphemism.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, χέζω (*chezo*, 'to shit'), is translated as "ease oneself, do one's need"; βινέω (*bineo*, 'to fuck') as "inire, coire, of illicit intercourse"; and λαικάζω (*laikazo*, 'to suck cocks') as "to wench".
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] Two condensed editions of LSJ were published by Oxford University Press and remain in print.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1843, the same year as the full lexicon's publication, *A Lexicon: Abridged from Liddell and Scott's Greek–English Lexicon*, sometimes called "the Little Liddell" was published.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, a reprint, re-typeset in 2007, of the 1909 edition is available from Simon Wallenberg Press.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1889, an intermediate edition of the lexicon, *An Intermediate Greek–English Lexicon*, was prepared on the basis of the seventh edition (1883) of LSJ.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] After the publication of the ninth edition in 1940, and shortly after the deaths of both Stuart Jones and McKenzie, the OUP maintained a list of *addenda et corrigenda* ("additions and corrections"), which was bound with subsequent printings.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] However, in 1968, these were replaced by a Supplement to the LSJ.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] Neither the *addenda* nor the Supplement has ever been merged into the main text, which still stands as originally composed by Liddell, Scott, Jones, and McKenzie.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement was initially edited by M.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] Glare, editor of the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* (not to be confused with Lewis and Short's *A Latin Dictionary*).
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] Since 1988, it has been edited by Glare and Anne A.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] As the title page of the *Lexicon* makes clear (and the prefaces to the main text and to the Supplement attest), this editorial work has been performed "with the cooperation of many scholars".
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement primarily takes the form of a list of additions and corrections to the main text, sorted by entry.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The supplemental entries are marked with signs to show the nature of the changes they call for.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] Thus, a user of the *Lexicon* can consult the Supplement after consulting the main text to see whether scholarship after Jones and McKenzie has provided any new information about a particular word.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] As of 2005, the most recent revision of the Supplement, published in 1996, contains 320 pages of corrections to the main text, as well as other materials.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The small "x" indicates that this word did not appear in the main text at all; "S.*fr*." refers to the collected fragmentary works of Sophocles.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] One interesting new source of lexicographic material in the revised Supplement is the Mycenean inscriptions.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The ninth edition of LSJ has been freely available in electronic form since 2007, having been digitized by the Perseus Project.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] Diogenes, a free software package, incorporates the Perseus data and allows easy offline consultation of LSJ on Mac OS X, Windows, and Linux platforms.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] Marcion is another open source application that includes the Perseus LSJ.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] For mobile devices, both the Kindle E-Ink and the iPhone/iPod Touch feature data ported from Perseus.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Android market also currently offers the intermediate LSJ as an offline downloadable app for free or for a small price.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] A CD-ROM version published and sold by Logos Bible Software also incorporates the Supplement's additions to the ninth edition of LSJ.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] A new online version of LSJ was released in 2011 by the Thesaurus Linguae Graecae (TLG).
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The TLG version corrects "a large number of typographical errors", and includes links to the extensive TLG textual corpus.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] A Kindle version, the "Complete Liddell & Scott's Lexicon with Inflections", is also available: it allows searches of most Classical Greek word-forms and supports a growing number of Ancient/Classical Greek texts for the device.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Lexicon has been translated into Modern Greek by Xenophon Moschos, ed.: Michael Konstantinidis and was published by Anestis Konstantinidis in 1904 with the title *H.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] Scott – Α.* Κωνσταντινίδου (Μέγα Λεξικόν τῆς Ἑλληνικῆς Γλώσσης).
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] Also, a supplement compiled by a group of Greek philologists.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] An Italian translation of the *Intermediate Liddell-Scott*, entitled *Dizionario illustrato Greco-Italiano* was published in 1975 by Le Monnier, edited by Q.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] LSJ was the basis of the project of John Chadwick and James Diggle at Cambridge to publish the *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* of 2021.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] Although it was initially conceived as a mere update of LSJ, the editors eventually decided to start afresh since they considered LSJ "too antiquated in concept, design and content".
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The CGL has a smaller scope than the LSJ (and also the *Brill Dictionary of Ancient Greek*), and is unlikely to replace it; however, it is still more comprehensive than the Middle Liddell, which it intends to replace.
[src:anthrax/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* uses contemporary language for its definitions and, unlike the LSJ, no longer elides the meaning of words considered offensive in Victorian times.
[src:anthrax/abscess] An **abscess** is a collection of pus that has built up within the tissue of the body, usually caused by bacterial infection.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Signs and symptoms of abscesses include redness, pain, warmth, and swelling.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The swelling may feel fluid-filled when pressed.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The area of redness often extends beyond the swelling.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Carbuncles and boils are types of abscess that often involve hair follicles, with carbuncles being larger.
[src:anthrax/abscess] A cyst is related to an abscess, but it contains a material other than pus, and a cyst has a clearly defined wall.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Abscesses can also form internally on internal organs and after surgery.
[src:anthrax/abscess] They are usually caused by a bacterial infection.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Often many different types of bacteria are involved in a single infection.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In many areas of the world, the most common bacteria present are *methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Skin abscesses in particular are overwhelmingly caused by *S. aureus*.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Rarely, parasites can cause abscesses; this is more common in the developing world.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Diagnosis of a skin abscess is usually made based on what it looks like and is confirmed by cutting it open.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Ultrasound imaging may be useful in cases in which the diagnosis is not clear.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In abscesses around the anus, computer tomography (CT) may be important to look for deeper infection.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Standard treatment for most skin or soft tissue abscesses is cutting it open and drainage.
[src:anthrax/abscess] There appears to be some benefit from also using antibiotics.
[src:anthrax/abscess] A small amount of evidence supports not packing the cavity that remains with gauze after drainage.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Closing this cavity right after draining it rather than leaving it open may speed healing without increasing the risk of the abscess returning.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Sucking out the pus with a needle is often not sufficient.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Skin abscesses are common and have become more common in recent years.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Risk factors include intravenous drug use, with rates reported as high as 65% among users.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In 2005, 3.2 million people went to American emergency departments for abscesses.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In Australia, around 13,000 people were hospitalized in 2008 with the condition.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Abscesses may occur in any tissue, but most frequently within the skin surface (where they may be superficial pustules known as boils or deep skin abscesses), in the lungs, brain, teeth, kidneys, and tonsils.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Major complications may include spreading of the abscess material to adjacent or remote tissues, and extensive regional tissue death (gangrene).
[src:anthrax/abscess] The main symptoms and signs of a skin abscess are redness, heat, swelling, pain, and loss of function.
[src:anthrax/abscess] There may also be high temperature (fever) and chills.
[src:anthrax/abscess] If superficial, abscesses may be fluctuant when palpated; this wave-like motion is caused by movement of the pus inside the abscess.
[src:anthrax/abscess] An internal abscess is more difficult to identify and depends on the location of the abscess and the type of infection.
[src:anthrax/abscess] General signs include pain in the affected area, a high temperature, and generally feeling unwell.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Internal abscesses rarely heal themselves, so prompt medical attention is indicated if such an abscess is suspected.
[src:anthrax/abscess] An abscess can potentially be fatal depending on where it is located.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Risk factors for abscess formation include intravenous drug use.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Another possible risk factor is a prior history of disc herniation or other spinal abnormality, though this has not been proven.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Abscesses are caused by bacterial infection, parasites, or foreign substances.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Bacterial infection is the most common cause, particularly *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The more invasive methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA) may also be a source of infection, though it is much rarer.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Among spinal subdural abscesses, methicillin-sensitive *S. aureus* is the most common organism involved.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Rarely parasites can cause abscesses, and this is more common in the developing world.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Specific parasites known to do this include dracunculiasis and myiasis.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In immunocompromised people, and particularly those with AIDS, *Toxoplasma gondii* is a frequent cause of widespread abscesses throughout the body, including in the brain.
[src:anthrax/abscess] An abscess may form anywhere that bacteria can get through the skin, including insect bites, lacerations, puncture wounds, scrapes, IV injection sites, and other small surface-level injuries.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The overwhelming majority of skin abscesses are caused by *Staphylococcus aureus* (methicillin-susceptible or methicillin-resistant), with some studies showing over 90% of documented and cultured skin abscesses being caused by this organism.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Anorectal abscesses can be caused by non-specific obstruction and ensuing infection of the glandular crypts inside the anus or rectum.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Other causes include cancer, trauma, or inflammatory bowel diseases.
[src:anthrax/abscess] An *incisional abscess* develops as a complication secondary to a surgical incision.
[src:anthrax/abscess] It presents as redness and warmth at the margins of the incision with purulent drainage.
[src:anthrax/abscess] If the diagnosis is uncertain, the wound should be aspirated with a needle, with aspiration of pus confirming the diagnosis and availing for Gram stain and bacterial culture.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The cause can be from trauma, surgery, an infection, or a pre-existing condition.
[src:anthrax/abscess] An abscess is a buildup of pus surrounded by normal body tissue.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In most cases, abscesses are caused by an infectious species of bacteria, and they function to wall off the infection from uninfected tissues.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Organisms or foreign materials destroy the local cells, which results in the release of cytokines.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The cytokines trigger an inflammatory response, which draws large numbers of white blood cells to the area and increases the regional blood flow.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The final structure of the abscess is an abscess wall, or capsule, formed by adjacent healthy cells in an attempt to keep the pus from infecting neighboring structures.
[src:anthrax/abscess] However, such encapsulation tends to prevent immune cells from attacking bacteria in the pus or from reaching the causative organism or foreign object.
[src:anthrax/abscess] An abscess is a localized collection of pus (purulent inflammatory tissue) caused by suppuration buried in a tissue, an organ, or a confined space, lined by the pyogenic membrane.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Ultrasound imaging can help in a diagnosis.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Abscesses may be classified as either *skin abscesses* or *internal abscesses*.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Skin abscesses are common; internal abscesses tend to be harder to diagnose and more serious.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Skin abscesses are also called cutaneous or subcutaneous abscesses.
[src:anthrax/abscess] For those with a history of intravenous drug use, an X-ray is recommended before treatment to verify that no needle fragments are present.
[src:anthrax/abscess] If there is also a fever present in this population, infectious endocarditis should be considered.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Abscesses should be differentiated from empyemas, which are accumulations of pus in a preexisting, rather than a newly formed, anatomical cavity.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Other conditions that can cause similar symptoms include: cellulitis, a sebaceous cyst, and necrotising fasciitis.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Cellulitis typically also has an erythematous reaction, but does not confer any purulent drainage.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The standard treatment for an uncomplicated skin or soft-tissue abscess is the incision and drainage procedure.
[src:anthrax/abscess] There does not appear to be any benefit from also using antibiotics in most cases.
[src:anthrax/abscess] A small amount of evidence did not find a benefit from packing the abscess with gauze.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The abscess should be inspected to see if foreign objects are the cause, which may require their removal.
[src:anthrax/abscess] If foreign objects are not the cause, incising and draining the abscess is standard treatment.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In most cases, a localized injection of lidocaine and epinephrine precedes the incision, to suppress pain.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Most people with an uncomplicated skin abscess should not use antibiotics.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Antibiotics in addition to standard incision and drainage are recommended in persons with severe abscesses, many sites of infection, rapid disease progression, the presence of cellulitis, symptoms indicating bacterial illness throughout the body, or a health condition causing immunosuppression.
[src:anthrax/abscess] People who are very young or very old may also need antibiotics.
[src:anthrax/abscess] If the abscess does not heal only with incision and drainage, or if the abscess is in a place that is difficult to drain, such as the face, hands, or genitals, then antibiotics may be indicated.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In those cases of abscess which do require antibiotic treatment, *Staphylococcus aureus* bacteria are a common cause and an anti-staphylococcus antibiotic such as flucloxacillin or dicloxacillin is used.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The Infectious Diseases Society of America advises that the draining of an abscess is not enough to address community-acquired methicillin-resistant *Staphylococcus aureus* (MRSA).
[src:anthrax/abscess] In those cases, traditional antibiotics may be ineffective.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Alternative antibiotics effective against community-acquired MRSA often include clindamycin, doxycycline, minocycline, and trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The American College of Emergency Physicians advises that typical cases of abscess from MRSA get no benefit from having antibiotic treatment in addition to the standard treatment.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Culturing the wound is not needed if standard follow-up care can be provided after the incision and drainage.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Performing a wound culture is unnecessary because it rarely gives information that can be used to guide treatment.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In North America, after drainage, an abscess cavity is usually packed, often with special iodoform-treated cloth.
[src:anthrax/abscess] This is done to absorb and neutralize any remaining exudate as well as to promote draining and prevent premature closure.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Prolonged draining is thought to promote healing.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The hypothesis is that though the heart's pumping action can deliver immune and regenerative cells to the edge of an injury, an abscess is by definition a void in which no blood vessels are present.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Packing is thought to provide a wicking action that continuously draws beneficial factors and cells from the body into the void that must be healed.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Discharge is then absorbed by cutaneous bandages, and further wicking is promoted by changing these bandages regularly.
[src:anthrax/abscess] However, evidence from emergency medicine literature reports that packing wounds after draining, especially smaller wounds, causes pain to the person and does not decrease the rate of recurrence, nor bring faster healing, or fewer physician visits.
[src:anthrax/abscess] More recently, several North American hospitals have opted for less-invasive loop drainage over standard drainage and wound packing.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In one study of 143 pediatric outcomes, a failure rate of 1.4% was reported in the loop group versus 10.5% in the packing group (P<.030), while a separate study reported a 5.5% failure rate among the loop group.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Closing an abscess immediately after draining it appears to speed healing without increasing the risk of recurrence.
[src:anthrax/abscess] This may not apply to anorectal abscesses, as while they may heal faster, there may be a higher rate of recurrence than those left open.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Appendiceal abscesses are complications of appendicitis, where there is an infected mass on the appendix.
[src:anthrax/abscess] This condition is estimated to occur in 2–10% of appendicitis cases and is usually treated by surgical removal of the appendix (appendicectomy).
[src:anthrax/abscess] Even without treatment, skin abscesses rarely result in death, as they will naturally break through the skin.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Other types of abscesses are more dangerous.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Brain abscesses may be fatal if untreated.
[src:anthrax/abscess] When treated, the mortality rate decreases to 5–10%, but it is higher if the abscess ruptures.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In 2005, in the United States, 3.2 million people went to the emergency department for an abscess.
[src:anthrax/abscess] In Australia, around 13,000 people were hospitalized in 2008 for the disease.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The Latin medical aphorism "*ubi pus, ibi evacua*" expresses "where there is pus, there evacuate it" and is classical advice in the culture of Western medicine.
[src:anthrax/abscess] Needle exchange programmes often administer or provide referrals for abscess treatment to injection drug users as part of a harm reduction public health strategy.
[src:anthrax/abscess] An abscess is so called "abscess" because there is an *abscessus* (a going away or departure) of portions of the animal tissue from each other to make room for the suppurated matter lodged between them.
[src:anthrax/abscess] The word carbuncle is believed to have originated from the Latin: *carbunculus*, originally a small coal; diminutive of *carbon-*, *carbo*: charcoal or ember, but also a carbuncle stone, "precious stones of a red or fiery colour", usually garnets.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] It has key regulatory roles in essentially all cells.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] It is the most polyphyletic known enzyme: six distinct classes have been described, all catalyzing the same reaction but representing unrelated gene families with no known sequence or structural homology.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The best known class of adenylyl cyclases is class III or AC-III (Roman numerals are used for classes).
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] AC-III occurs widely in eukaryotes and has important roles in many human tissues.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] All classes of adenylyl cyclase catalyse the conversion of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to 3',5'-cyclic AMP (cAMP) and pyrophosphate.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Magnesium ions are generally required and appear to be closely involved in the enzymatic mechanism.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The cAMP produced by AC then serves as a regulatory signal via specific cAMP-binding proteins, either transcription factors, enzymes (e.g., cAMP-dependent kinases), or ion transporters.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The first class of adenylyl cyclases occur in many bacteria including *E. coli* (as CyaA P00936 [unrelated to the Class II enzyme]).
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] This was the first class of AC to be characterized.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] It was observed that *E. coli* deprived of glucose produce cAMP that serves as an internal signal to activate expression of genes for importing and metabolizing other sugars. cAMP exerts this effect by binding the transcription factor CRP, also known as CAP.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Class I AC's are large cytosolic enzymes (~100 kDa) with a large regulatory domain (~50 kDa) that indirectly senses glucose levels.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] As of 2012, no crystal structure is available for class I AC.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Some indirect structural information is available for this class.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] It is known that the N-terminal half is the catalytic portion, and that it requires two Mg2+ ions.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] S103, S113, D114, D116 and W118 are the five absolutely essential residues.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The class I catalytic domain (Pfam PF12633) belongs to the same superfamily (Pfam CL0260) as the palm domain of DNA polymerase beta (Pfam PF18765).
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Aligning its sequence onto the structure onto a related archaeal CCA tRNA nucleotidyltransferase (PDB: 1R89) allows for assignment of the residues to specific functions: γ-phosphate binding, structural stabilization, DxD motif for metal ion binding, and finally ribose binding.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] These adenylyl cyclases are toxins secreted by pathogenic bacteria such as *Bacillus anthracis*, *Bordetella pertussis*, *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, and *Vibrio vulnificus* during infections.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] These bacteria also secrete proteins that enable the AC-II to enter host cells, where the exogenous AC activity undermines normal cellular processes.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The genes for Class II ACs are known as cyaA, one of which is anthrax toxin.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Several crystal structures are known for AC-II enzymes.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] These adenylyl cyclases are the most familiar based on extensive study due to their important roles in human health.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] They are also found in some bacteria, notably *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* where they appear to have a key role in pathogenesis.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Most AC-III's are integral membrane proteins involved in transducing extracellular signals into intracellular responses.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] A Nobel Prize was awarded to Earl Sutherland in 1971 for discovering the key role of AC-III in human liver, where adrenaline indirectly stimulates AC to mobilize stored energy in the "fight or flight" response.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The effect of adrenaline is via a G protein signaling cascade, which transmits chemical signals from outside the cell across the membrane to the inside of the cell (cytoplasm).
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The outside signal (in this case, adrenaline) binds to a receptor, which transmits a signal to the G protein, which transmits a signal to adenylyl cyclase, which transmits a signal by converting adenosine triphosphate to cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP). cAMP is known as a second messenger.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Cyclic AMP is an important molecule in eukaryotic signal transduction, a so-called second messenger.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Adenylyl cyclases are often activated or inhibited by G proteins, which are coupled to membrane receptors and thus can respond to hormonal or other stimuli.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Following activation of adenylyl cyclase, the resulting cAMP acts as a second messenger by interacting with and regulating other proteins such as protein kinase A and cyclic nucleotide-gated ion channels.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Photoactivated adenylyl cyclase (PAC) was discovered in *Euglena gracilis* and can be expressed in other organisms through genetic manipulation.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Shining blue light on a cell containing PAC activates it and abruptly increases the rate of conversion of ATP to cAMP.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] This is a useful technique for researchers in neuroscience because it allows them to quickly increase the intracellular cAMP levels in particular neurons, and to study the effect of that increase in neural activity on the behavior of the organism.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] A green-light activated rhodopsin adenylyl cyclase (CaRhAC) has recently been engineered by modifying the nucleotide binding pocket of rhodopsin guanylyl cyclase.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Most class III adenylyl cyclases are transmembrane proteins with 12 transmembrane segments.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The protein is organized with 6 transmembrane segments, then the C1 cytoplasmic domain, then another 6 membrane segments, and then a second cytoplasmic domain called C2.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The important parts for function are the N-terminus and the C1 and C2 regions.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The C1a and C2a subdomains are homologous and form an intramolecular 'dimer' that forms the active site.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] In *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* and many other bacterial cases, the AC-III polypeptide is only half as long, comprising one 6-transmembrane domain followed by a cytoplasmic domain, but two of these form a functional homodimer that resembles the mammalian architecture with two active sites.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] In non-animal class III ACs, the catalytic cytoplasmic domain is seen associated with other (not necessarily transmembrane) domains.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Class III adenylyl cyclase domains can be further divided into four subfamilies, termed class IIIa through IIId.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Animal membrane-bound ACs belong to class IIIa.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The reaction happens with two metal cofactors (Mg or Mn) coordinated to the two aspartate residues on C1.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] They perform a nucleophilic attack of the 3'-OH group of the ribose on the α-phosphoryl group of ATP.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The two lysine and aspartate residues on C2 selects ATP over GTP for the substrate, so that the enzyme is not a guanylyl cyclase.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] A pair of arginine and asparagine residues on C2 stabilizes the transition state.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] In many proteins, these residues are nevertheless mutated while retaining the adenylyl cyclase activity.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] These are also sometimes called simply AC1, AC2, etc., and, somewhat confusingly, sometimes Roman numerals are used for these isoforms that all belong to the overall AC class III.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] They differ mainly in how they are regulated, and are differentially expressed in various tissues throughout mammalian development.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Adenylyl cyclase is regulated by G proteins, which can be found in the monomeric form or the heterotrimeric form, consisting of three subunits.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Adenylyl cyclase activity is controlled by heterotrimeric G proteins.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The inactive or inhibitory form exists when the complex consists of alpha, beta, and gamma subunits, with GDP bound to the alpha subunit.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] In order to become active, a ligand must bind to the receptor and cause a conformational change.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] This conformational change causes the alpha subunit to dissociate from the complex and become bound to GTP.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] This G-alpha-GTP complex then binds to adenylyl cyclase and causes activation and the release of cAMP.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Since a good signal requires the help of enzymes, which turn on and off signals quickly, there must also be a mechanism in which adenylyl cyclase deactivates and inhibits cAMP.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] The deactivation of the active G-alpha-GTP complex is accomplished rapidly by GTP hydrolysis due to the reaction being catalyzed by the intrinsic enzymatic activity of GTPase located in the alpha subunit.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] In neurons, calcium-sensitive adenylyl cyclases are located next to calcium ion channels for faster reaction to Ca2+ influx; they are suspected of playing an important role in learning processes.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] This is supported by the fact that adenylyl cyclases are *coincidence detectors*, meaning that they are activated only by several different signals occurring together.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] In peripheral cells and tissues adenylyl cyclases appear to form molecular complexes with specific receptors and other signaling proteins in an isoform-specific manner.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Individual transmembrane adenylyl cyclase isoforms have been linked to numerous physiological functions.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Soluble adenylyl cyclase (sAC, AC10) has a critical role in sperm motility.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Adenylyl cyclase has been implicated in memory formation, functioning as a coincidence detector.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] AC-IV was first reported in the bacterium *Aeromonas hydrophila*, and the structure of the AC-IV from *Yersinia pestis* has been reported.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] These are the smallest of the AC enzyme classes; the AC-IV (CyaB) from *Yersinia* is a dimer of 19 kDa subunits with no known regulatory components (PDB: 2FJT).
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] AC-IV forms a superfamily with mammalian thiamine-triphosphatase called CYTH (CyaB, thiamine triphosphatase).
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] These forms of AC have been reported in specific bacteria (*Prevotella ruminicola* O68902 and *Rhizobium etli* Q8KY20, respectively) and have not been extensively characterized.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] There are a few extra members (~400 in Pfam) known to be in class VI.
[src:anthrax/adenylate-cyclase] Class VI enzymes possess a catalytic core similar to the one in Class III.
[src:anthrax/adrien-loir] From 1882 to 1888 Loir was an assistant in Pasteur's laboratory in Paris, where he performed research of swine fever.
[src:anthrax/adrien-loir] In 1886, he installed the first anti-rabies clinic in Saint Petersburg.
[src:anthrax/adrien-loir] Between 1888 and 1893 he made two journeys to Australia to conduct research of anthrax and pleuropneumonia.
[src:anthrax/adrien-loir] While there, he investigated the use of chicken cholera bacillus in an attempt to eradicate the country's rabbit infestation.
[src:anthrax/adrien-loir] In 1893 he founded the Pasteur Institute of Tunisia, and for several years was a professor of hygiene and bacteriology at the colonial school in Tunis.
[src:anthrax/adrien-loir] In 1906 he traveled to Canada, where he demonstrated that the equine disease, dourine is caused by the parasite *trypanosoma equiperdum*.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] An **aerosol** is a suspension of fine solid particles or liquid droplets in air or another gas.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Aerosols can be generated from natural or human causes.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The scientific term *aerosol* refers to the mixture of particulates in gas, and not to the particulate matter alone.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The liquid or solid particles in an aerosol have diameters typically less than 1 μm.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Larger particles with a significant settling speed make the mixture a suspension, although the distinction is not clear.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Examples of natural aerosols are fog, mist, and dust from geological or biological sources.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Certain infections spread by means of small droplets in the breath, sometimes called bioaerosols.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Volcanic aerosol forms in the stratosphere after an eruption as droplets of sulfuric acid that can prevail for up to two years, and reflect sunlight, lowering temperature.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Desert dust, mineral particles blown to high altitudes, absorb heat and may be responsible for inhibiting storm cloud formation.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] In everyday language, *aerosol* often refers to a dispensing system that delivers a consumer product from a spray can.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Other examples of human caused aerosols include perfume from atomizers, medical treatments for respiratory illnesses, dust from material or industrial sources, smoke, irrigation mist, sprayed pesticides, particulate air pollutants, and mist from the discharge at hydroelectric dams.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Human-made sulfate aerosols, primarily from burning oil and coal, affect the behavior of clouds.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] When aerosols absorb pollutants, it facilitates the deposition of pollutants to the surface of the earth as well as to bodies of water.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] This has the potential to be damaging to both the environment and human health.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Ship tracks are clouds that form around the exhaust released by ships into the still ocean air.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Water molecules collect around the tiny particles (aerosols) from exhaust to form a cloud seed.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] More and more water accumulates on the seed until a visible cloud is formed.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] In the case of ship tracks, the cloud seeds are stretched over a long narrow path where the wind has blown the ship's exhaust, so the resulting clouds resemble long strings over the ocean.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The warming caused by human-produced greenhouse gases has been somewhat offset by the cooling effect of human-produced aerosols.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] In 2020, regulations on fuel significantly cut sulfur dioxide emissions from international shipping by approximately 80%, leading to an unexpected global geoengineering termination shock.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Aerosol is defined as a suspension system of solid or liquid particles in a gas.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] An aerosol includes both the particles and the suspending gas, which is usually air.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Meteorologists and climatologists often refer to them as particle matter, while the classification in sizes ranges like PM2.5 or PM10, is useful in the field of atmospheric pollution as these size range play a role in ascertain the harmful effects in human health.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Donnan presumably first used the term *aerosol* during World War I to describe an aero-solution, clouds of microscopic particles in air.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] This term developed analogously to the term hydrosol, a colloid system with water as the dispersed medium.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] *Primary aerosols* contain particles introduced directly into the gas; *secondary aerosols* form through gas-to-particle conversion.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Key aerosol groups include sulfates, organic carbon, black carbon, nitrates, mineral dust, and sea salt, they usually clump together to form a complex mixture.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Various types of aerosol, classified according to physical form and how they were generated, include dust, fume, mist, smoke and fog.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] There are several measures of aerosol concentration.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Environmental science and environmental health often use the *mass concentration* (*M*), defined as the mass of particulate matter per unit volume, in units such as μg/m3.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Also commonly used is the *number concentration* (*N*), the number of particles per unit volume, in units such as number per m3 or number per cm3.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Particle size has a major influence on particle properties, and the aerosol particle radius or diameter (*dp*) is a key property used to characterise aerosols.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] A *monodisperse* aerosol, producible in the laboratory, contains particles of uniform size.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Most aerosols, however, as *polydisperse* colloidal systems, exhibit a range of particle sizes.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Liquid droplets are almost always nearly spherical, but scientists use an *equivalent diameter* to characterize the properties of various shapes of solid particles, some very irregular.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The equivalent diameter is the diameter of a spherical particle with the same value of some physical property as the irregular particle.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The *equivalent volume diameter* (*de*) is defined as the diameter of a sphere of the same volume as that of the irregular particle.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Also commonly used is the aerodynamic diameter, *da*.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, that originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Although all hydrometeors, solid and liquid, can be described as aerosols, a distinction is commonly made between such dispersions (i.e. clouds and precipitation) containing relatively large water drops or ice crystals, and aerosol particles.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The presence of aerosols in the Earth's atmosphere can influence its climate, as well as human health.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Volcanic eruptions release large amounts of sulphuric acid, hydrogen sulfide and hydrochloric acid into the atmosphere.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] These gases represent aerosols and eventually return to earth as acid rain, having a number of adverse effects on the environment and human life.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Aerosols interact with the Earth's energy budget in two ways, directly and indirectly.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Aerosol particles with an effective diameter smaller than 10 μm can enter the bronchi, while the ones with an effective diameter smaller than 2.5 μm can enter as far as the gas exchange region in the lungs, which can be hazardous to human health.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] For a monodisperse aerosol, a single number—the particle diameter—suffices to describe the size of the particles.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] However, more complicated particle-size distributions describe the sizes of the particles in a polydisperse aerosol.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] This distribution defines the relative amounts of particles, sorted according to size.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] One approach to defining the particle size distribution uses a list of the sizes of every particle in a sample.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] However, this approach proves tedious to ascertain in aerosols with millions of particles and awkward to use.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Another approach splits the size range into intervals and finds the number (or proportion) of particles in each interval.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The particle size distribution can be approximated.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The normal distribution usually does not suitably describe particle size distributions in aerosols because of the skewness associated with a long tail of larger particles.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Also for a quantity that varies over a large range, as many aerosol sizes do, the width of the distribution implies negative particles sizes, which is not physically realistic.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] However, the normal distribution can be suitable for some aerosols, such as test aerosols, certain pollen grains and spores.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The log-normal distribution has no negative values, can cover a wide range of values, and fits many observed size distributions reasonably well.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] For low values of the Reynolds number (<1), true for most aerosol motion, Stokes' law describes the force of resistance on a solid spherical particle in a fluid.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] However, Stokes' law is only valid when the velocity of the gas at the surface of the particle is zero.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] For small particles (< 1 μm) that characterize aerosols, however, this assumption fails.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] To account for this failure, one can introduce the Cunningham correction factor, always greater than 1.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] This allows us to calculate the terminal velocity of a particle undergoing gravitational settling in still air.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] is the terminal settling velocity of the particle.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The terminal velocity can also be derived for other kinds of forces.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] If Stokes' law holds, then the resistance to motion is directly proportional to speed.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] To account for the effect of the shape of non-spherical particles, a correction factor known as the *dynamic shape factor* is applied to Stokes' law.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The aerodynamic diameter of an irregular particle is defined as the diameter of the spherical particle with a density of 1000 kg/m3 and the same settling velocity as the irregular particle.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] One can apply the aerodynamic diameter to particulate pollutants or to inhaled drugs to predict where in the respiratory tract such particles deposit.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Pharmaceutical companies typically use aerodynamic diameter, not geometric diameter, to characterize particles in inhalable drugs.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The previous discussion focused on single aerosol particles.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] In contrast, *aerosol dynamics* explains the evolution of complete aerosol populations.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The concentrations of particles will change over time as a result of many processes.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] External processes that move particles outside a volume of gas under study include diffusion, gravitational settling, and electric charges and other external forces that cause particle migration.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] A second set of processes internal to a given volume of gas include particle formation (nucleation), evaporation, chemical reaction, and coagulation.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] A differential equation called the *Aerosol General Dynamic Equation* (GDE) characterizes the evolution of the number density of particles in an aerosol due to these processes.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] As particles and droplets in an aerosol collide with one another, they may undergo coalescence or aggregation.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] This process leads to a change in the aerosol particle-size distribution, with the mode increasing in diameter as total number of particles decreases.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] On occasion, particles may shatter apart into numerous smaller particles; however, this process usually occurs primarily in particles too large for consideration as aerosols.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] where $\lambda$ is the mean free path of the suspending gas and d is the diameter of the particle.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] For particles in the *free molecular regime*, *Kn* >> 1; particles small compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] In this regime, particles interact with the suspending gas through a series of "ballistic" collisions with gas molecules.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] As such, they behave similarly to gas molecules, tending to follow streamlines and diffusing rapidly through Brownian motion.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] where *a* is the particle radius, *P*∞ and *PA* are the pressures far from the droplet and at the surface of the droplet respectively, *kb* is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the temperature, *CA* is mean thermal velocity and *α* is mass accommodation coefficient.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The derivation of this equation assumes constant pressure and constant diffusion coefficient.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Particles are in the *continuum regime* when Kn << 1.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] In this regime, the particles are big compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas, meaning that the suspending gas acts as a continuous fluid flowing round the particle.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The *transition regime* contains all the particles in between the free molecular and continuum regimes or *Kn* ≈ 1.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The forces experienced by a particle are a complex combination of interactions with individual gas molecules and macroscopic interactions.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] where *I*cont is the mass flux in the continuum regime.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] This formula is called the Fuchs-Sutugin interpolation formula.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] These equations do not take into account the heat release effect.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Aerosol partitioning theory governs condensation on and evaporation from an aerosol surface, respectively.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Condensation of mass causes the mode of the particle-size distributions of the aerosol to increase; conversely, evaporation causes the mode to decrease.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Nucleation is the process of forming aerosol mass from the condensation of a gaseous precursor, specifically a vapor.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Net condensation of the vapor requires supersaturation, a partial pressure greater than its vapor pressure.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Chemical reactions may increase the partial pressure of a gas or lower its vapor pressure.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The addition of additional vapor to the system may lower the equilibrium vapor pressure according to Raoult's law.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] There are two types of nucleation processes.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Gases preferentially condense onto surfaces of pre-existing aerosol particles, known as **heterogeneous nucleation**.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] This process causes the diameter at the mode of particle-size distribution to increase with constant number concentration.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] With sufficiently high supersaturation and no suitable surfaces, particles may condense in the absence of a pre-existing surface, known as **homogeneous nucleation**.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] This results in the addition of very small, rapidly growing particles to the particle-size distribution.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Water coats particles in aerosols, making them *activated*, usually in the context of forming a cloud droplet (such as natural cloud seeding by aerosols from trees in a forest).
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Following the Kelvin equation (based on the curvature of liquid droplets), smaller particles need a higher ambient relative humidity to maintain equilibrium than larger particles do.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] where $p_{s}$ is the saturation vapor pressure above a particle at equilibrium (around a curved liquid droplet), *p*0 is the saturation vapor pressure (flat surface of the same liquid) and *S* is the saturation ratio.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] where *rp* droplet radius, *σ* surface tension of droplet, *ρ* density of liquid, *M* molar mass, *T* temperature, and *R* molar gas constant.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Aerosols can either be measured in-situ or with remote sensing techniques either ground-based on airborne-based.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Particles can deposit in the nose, mouth, pharynx and larynx (the head airways region), deeper within the respiratory tract (from the trachea to the terminal bronchioles), or in the alveolar region.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The location of deposition of aerosol particles within the respiratory system strongly determines the health effects of exposure to such aerosols.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] This phenomenon led people to invent aerosol samplers that select a subset of the aerosol particles that reach certain parts of the respiratory system.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Examples of these subsets of the particle-size distribution of an aerosol, important in occupational health, include the inhalable, thoracic, and respirable fractions.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The fraction that can enter each part of the respiratory system depends on the deposition of particles in the upper parts of the airway.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The inhalable fraction of particles, defined as the proportion of particles originally in the air that can enter the nose or mouth, depends on external wind speed and direction and on the particle-size distribution by aerodynamic diameter.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The thoracic fraction is the proportion of the particles in ambient aerosol that can reach the thorax or chest region.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The respirable fraction is the proportion of particles in the air that can reach the alveolar region.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] To measure the respirable fraction of particles in air, a pre-collector is used with a sampling filter.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The pre-collector excludes particles as the airways remove particles from inhaled air.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The sampling filter collects the particles for measurement.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] It is common to use cyclonic separation for the pre-collector, but other techniques include impactors, horizontal elutriators, and large pore membrane filters.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] Two alternative size-selective criteria, often used in atmospheric monitoring, are PM10 and PM2.5.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] PM10 is defined by ISO as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 10 μm aerodynamic diameter* and PM2.5 as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 2.5 μm aerodynamic diameter*.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] PM10 corresponds to the "thoracic convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, Clause 6; PM2.5 corresponds to the "high-risk respirable convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, 7.1.
[src:anthrax/aerosol] The United States Environmental Protection Agency replaced the older standards for particulate matter based on Total Suspended Particulate with another standard based on PM10 in 1987 and then introduced standards for PM2.5 (also known as fine particulate matter) in 1997.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The term was coined in 1877 by Viennese surgeon Albert Theodor Billroth (1829–1894), from Ancient Greek στρεπτός (*streptós*), meaning "twisted", and κόκκος (*kókkos*), meaning "grain".
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] In 1984, many bacteria formerly grouped in the genus *Streptococcus* were separated out into the genera *Enterococcus* and *Lactococcus*.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Currently, over 50 species are recognised in this genus.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Streptococci have been divided into six groups on the basis of their 16S rDNA sequences: *S. anginosus, S. gallolyticus, S. mitis, S. mutans, S. pyogenes* and *S. salivarius*.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The 16S groups have been confirmed by whole genome sequencing (see figure).
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The important pathogens *S. pneumoniae* and *S. pyogenes* belong to the *S. mitis* and *S. pyogenes* groups, respectively, while the causative agent of dental caries, *Streptococcus mutans*, is basal to the *Streptococcus* group.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Recent technological advances have resulted in an increase of available genome sequences for *Streptococcus* species, allowing for more robust and reliable phylogenetic and comparative genomic analyses to be conducted.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The results revealed the presence of two main clades at the highest level within *Streptococcus*, termed the "Mitis-Suis" and "Pyogenes-Equinus-Mutans" clades.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The "Mitis-Suis" main clade comprises the Suis subclade and the Mitis clade, which encompasses the Angiosus, Pneumoniae, Gordonii and Parasanguinis subclades.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The second main clade, the "Pyogenes-Equinus-Mutans", includes the Pyogenes, Mutans, Salivarius, Equinus, Sobrinus, Halotolerans, Porci, Entericus and Orisratti subclades.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] A summary diagram showing the overall relationships among the *Streptococcus* based on these studies is depicted in a figure on this page.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] In clinical microbiology, species of streptococci are classified by phenotype using fast and simple biochemical tests.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The first step is to test for hemolytic properties.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Alpha-hemolytic species cause oxidization of iron in hemoglobin molecules within red blood cells, giving it a greenish color on blood agar.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Beta-hemolytic species cause complete rupture of red blood cells.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] On blood agar, this appears as wide areas clear of blood cells surrounding bacterial colonies.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Gamma-hemolytic species cause no hemolysis.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Beta-hemolytic streptococci are further classified by Lancefield grouping, a serotype classification (that is, describing specific carbohydrates present on the bacterial cell wall).
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The 21 described serotypes are named Lancefield groups A to W (excluding E, I and J).
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] This system of classification was developed by Rebecca Lancefield, a scientist at Rockefeller University.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] In the medical setting, the most important groups are the alpha-hemolytic streptococci *S. pneumoniae* and *Streptococcus* *viridans*groups, and the beta-hemolytic streptococci of Lancefield groups A and B (also known as "group A strep" and "group B strep").
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] When alpha-hemolysis (α-hemolysis) is present, a blood based agar under the colony will appear dark and greenish due to the conversion of hemoglobin to green biliverdin.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] *Streptococcus pneumoniae* and a group of oral streptococci (*Streptococcus viridans* or viridans streptococci) display alpha-hemolysis.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Alpha-hemolysis is also termed incomplete hemolysis or partial hemolysis because the cell membranes of the red blood cells are left intact.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] This is also sometimes called green hemolysis because of the color change in the agar.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The viridans streptococci are a large group of commensal bacteria that are either alpha-hemolytic, producing a green coloration on blood agar plates (hence the name "viridans", from Latin *vĭrĭdis*, green), or nonhemolytic.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The "viridans" group is a wastebasket taxon.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] It incldues representatives of all six traditional 16S groups of the genus.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Beta-hemolysis (β-hemolysis), sometimes called complete hemolysis, is a complete lysis of red cells in the media around and under the colonies: the area appears lightened (yellow) and transparent.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Streptolysin, an exotoxin, is the enzyme produced by the bacteria which causes the complete lysis of red blood cells.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] There are two types of streptolysin: Streptolysin O (SLO) and streptolysin S (SLS).
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Streptolysin O is an oxygen-sensitive cytotoxin, secreted by most group A *Streptococcus* (GAS), and interacts with cholesterol in the membrane of eukaryotic cells (mainly red and white blood cells, macrophages, and platelets), and usually results in beta-hemolysis under the surface of blood agar.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Streptolysin S is an oxygen-stable cytotoxin also produced by most GAS strains which results in clearing on the surface of blood agar.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] SLS affects immune cells, including polymorphonuclear leukocytes and lymphocytes, and is thought to prevent the host immune system from clearing infection.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] *Streptococcus pyogenes*, or GAS, displays beta hemolysis.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Some beta-hemolytic species cause intense hemolysis when grown in close proximity with certain strains of *Staphylococcus*.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] *Streptococcus agalactiae* displays this property.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] *Clostridium perfringens* can be identified presumptively with this test.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] *Listeria monocytogenes* is also positive on sheep's blood agar.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Group A *S. pyogenes* is the causative agent in a wide range of group A streptococcal infections (GAS).
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] These infections may be noninvasive or invasive.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The noninvasive infections tend to be more common and less severe.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The most common of these infections include streptococcal pharyngitis (strep throat) and impetigo.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Scarlet fever is another example of Group A noninvasive infection.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The invasive infections caused by group A beta-hemolytic streptococci tend to be more severe and less common.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] This occurs when the bacterium is able to infect areas where it is not usually found, such as the blood and organs.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The diseases that may be caused include streptococcal toxic shock syndrome, necrotizing fasciitis, pneumonia, and bacteremia.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Globally, GAS has been estimated to cause more than 500,000 deaths every year, making it one of the world's leading pathogens.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Additional complications may be caused by GAS, namely acute rheumatic fever and acute glomerulonephritis.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Rheumatic fever, a disease that affects the joints, kidneys, and heart valves, is a consequence of untreated strep A infection caused not by the bacterium itself, but due to the antibodies created by the immune system to fight off the infection cross-reacting with other proteins in the body.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] This "cross-reaction" causes the body to essentially attack itself and leads to the damage above.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] GAS infection is generally diagnosed with a rapid strep test or by culture.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The United Kingdom has chosen to adopt a risk factor-based protocol, rather than the culture-based protocol followed in the US.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] This protocol results in the administration of intrapartum antibiotics to 15–20% of pregnant women and the prevention of 65–70% of cases of early onset GBS sepsis.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] This group includes *S. equi*, which causes strangles in horses, and *S. zooepidemicus* — *S. equi* is a clonal descendant or biovar of the ancestral *S. zooepidemicus* — which causes infections in several species of mammals, including cattle and horses.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] *S. dysgalactiae subsp. dysgalactiae* is also a member of group C, beta-haemolytic streptococci that can cause pharyngitis and other pyogenic infections similar to group A streptococci.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Group C streptococcal bacteria are considered zoonotic pathogens, meaning infection can be passed from animal to human.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Many former group D streptococci have been reclassified and placed in the genus *Enterococcus* (including *E. faecalis*, *E. faecium*, *E. durans*, and *E. avium*).
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] For example, *Streptococcus faecalis* is now *Enterococcus faecalis*.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] *E. faecalis* is sometimes alpha-hemolytic and *E. faecium* is sometimes beta hemolytic.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The remaining nonenterococcal group D species include *Streptococcus gallolyticus*, *Streptococcus bovis*, *Streptococcus equinus* and *Streptococcus suis*.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Nonhemolytic streptococci rarely cause illness.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] However, weakly hemolytic group D beta-hemolytic streptococci and *Listeria monocytogenes* (which is actually a gram-positive bacillus) should not be confused with nonhemolytic streptococci.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Group F streptococci were first described in 1934 by Long and Bliss among the "minute haemolytic streptococci".
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] They are also known as *Streptococcus anginosus* (according to the Lancefield classification system) or as members of the *S. milleri* group (according to the European system).
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] These streptococci are usually, but not exclusively, beta-hemolytic.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] *Streptococcus dysgalactiae subsp. canis* is the predominant subspecies encountered.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] It is a particularly common GGS in humans, although it is typically found on animals.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] *S. phocae* is a GGS subspecies that has been found in marine mammals and marine fish species.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] In marine mammals it has been mainly associated with meningoencephalitis, sepsis, and endocarditis, but is also associated with many other pathologies.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Its environmental reservoir and means of transmission in marine mammals is not well characterized.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Group G streptococci are also considered zoonotic pathogens.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Group H streptococci cause infections in medium-sized canines.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Group H streptococci rarely cause human illness unless a human has direct contact with the mouth of a canine.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] One of the most common ways this can be spread is human-to-canine, mouth-to-mouth contact.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] However, the canine may lick the human's hand and infection can be spread, as well.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] In clinical practice, the most common groups of *Streptococcus* can be distinguished by simple bench tests, such as the PYR test for group A streptococcus.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] There are also latex agglutination kits which can distinguish each of the main groups seen in clinical practice.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Streptococcal infections can be treated with antibiotics from the penicillin family.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Most commonly, penicillin or amoxicillin is used to treat infection due to beta hemolytic Streptococcus infections.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] These antibiotics work by disrupting peptidoglycan production in the cell wall.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Treatment most often occurs as a 10-day oral antibiotic cycle.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] For patients with penicillin allergies and those suffering from skin infections, clindamycin can be used.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Clindamycin works by disrupting protein synthesis within the cell.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The genomes of hundreds of species have been sequenced.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Most *Streptococcus* genomes are 1.8 to 2.3 Mb in size and encode 1,700 to 2,300 proteins.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Some important genomes are listed in the table.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] The four species shown in the table (*S. pyogenes, S. agalactiae, S. pneumoniae*, and *S. mutans*) have an average pairwise protein sequence identity of about 70%.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Bacteriophages have been described for many species of *Streptococcus*.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] 18 prophages have been described in *S. pneumoniae* that range in size from 38 to 41 kb in size, encoding from 42 to 66 genes each.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Some of the first *Streptococcus* phages discovered were Dp-1 and ω1 (alias ω-1).
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] In 1981 the Cp (Complutense phage 1, officially *Streptococcus virus Cp1*, *Picovirinae*) family was discovered with Cp-1 as its first member.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Dp-1 and Cp-1 infect both *S. pneumoniae* and *S. mitis*.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] However, the host ranges of most *Streptococcus* phages have not been investigated systematically.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Natural genetic transformation involves the transfer of DNA from one bacterium to another through the surrounding medium.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Transformation is a complex process dependent on the expression of numerous genes.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] To be capable of transformation a bacterium must enter a special physiologic state referred to as competence.
[src:anthrax/alpha-hemolytic-streptococci] Competence may allow the streptococcal pathogen to use external homologous DNA for recombinational repair of DNA damages caused by the host's oxidative attack.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the first clinical descriptions of cutaneous anthrax were given by Maret in 1752 and Fournier in 1769.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Before that, anthrax had been described only in historical accounts.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The German scientist Robert Koch was the first to identify *Bacillus anthracis* as the bacterium that causes anthrax.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax is spread by contact with the bacterium's spores, which often appear in infected animal products.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Contact includes inhalation, eating, or through an area of broken skin.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] It does not typically spread directly between people.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] At risk populations include people who work with animals or animal products and military personnel.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Diagnosis can be confirmed by finding antibodies or the toxin in the blood or by the culture of a sample from the infected site.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The anthrax vaccine is recommended for people at high risk of infection.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Immunizing animals against anthrax is recommended in areas where previous infections have occurred.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] A two-month course of antibiotics such as ciprofloxacin, levofloxacin and doxycycline after exposure can also prevent infection.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] If infection occurs, treatment is with antibiotics and possibly antitoxin.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The type and number of antibiotics used depend on the type of infection.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] An antitoxin is recommended for those with widespread infection.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] A rare disease, human anthrax is most common in Africa and central and southern Asia.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] It occurs more regularly in Southern Europe than elsewhere on the continent and is uncommon in Northern Europe and North America.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Globally, at least 2,000 cases occur a year, with about two cases a year in the United States.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Skin infections represent more than 95% of cases.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Without treatment the risk of death from skin anthrax is 23.7%.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] For intestinal infection the risk of death is 25 to 75%, while respiratory anthrax has a mortality of 50 to 80%, even with treatment.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Until the 20th century, anthrax infections killed hundreds of thousands of people and animals each year.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In herbivorous animals, infection occurs when they eat or breathe in the spores while grazing.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Humans may become infected by killing and/or eating infected animals.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Several countries and non-state groups have developed anthrax as a weapon.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] It has been used in biowarfare and bioterrorism since 1916.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Likely delivery methods of weaponized anthrax include aerial dispersal or dispersal through livestock.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In World War II, it was developed and used by the Empire of Japan's Unit 731 against China, and researched by a British plan against Nazi Germany.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The Soviet, United States, and Iraqi biological weapons program developed weaponized strains.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In 1975, the Biological Weapons Convention prohibited the "development, production and stockpiling" of biological weapons.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] It has since been used in bioterrorism, including the 2001 anthrax attacks in the United States and an incident in 1993 by the Aum Shinrikyo group in Japan.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The English name comes from *anthrax* (ἄνθραξ), the Greek word for coal, possibly having Egyptian etymology, because of the characteristic black skin lesions people with a cutaneous anthrax infection develop.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The central black eschar surrounded by vivid red skin has long been recognised as typical of the disease.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The first recorded use of the word "anthrax" in English is in a 1398 translation of Bartholomaeus Anglicus's work **De proprietatibus rerum** (*On the Properties of Things*, 1240).
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax was historically known by a wide variety of names, indicating its symptoms, location, and groups considered most vulnerable to infection.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] They include Siberian plague, Cumberland disease, charbon, splenic fever, malignant edema, woolsorter's disease and **la maladie de Bradford**.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Cutaneous anthrax, also known as hide-porter's disease, is when anthrax occurs on the skin.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] It is the most common (>90% of cases) and least dangerous form (low mortality with treatment, 23.7% mortality without).
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Cutaneous anthrax presents as a boil-like skin lesion that eventually forms an ulcer with a black center (eschar).
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The black eschar often shows up as a large, painless, necrotic ulcer (beginning as an irritating and itchy skin lesion or blister that is dark and usually concentrated as a black dot, (somewhat resembling bread mold) at the site of infection.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In general, cutaneous infections form within the site of spore penetration two to five days after exposure.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Unlike bruises or most other lesions, cutaneous anthrax infections normally do not cause pain.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Nearby lymph nodes may become infected, reddened, swollen, and painful.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] A scab forms over the lesion soon, and falls off in a few weeks.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Cutaneous anthrax is typically caused when *B. anthracis* spores enter through cuts on the skin.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] This form is found most commonly when humans handle infected animals and/or animal products.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In December 2009, an outbreak of anthrax occurred among injecting heroin users in the Glasgow and Stirling areas of Scotland, resulting in 14 deaths.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] It was the first documented non-occupational human anthrax outbreak in the UK since 1960.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The source of the anthrax is believed to have been dilution of the heroin with bone meal in Afghanistan.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Injected anthrax may have symptoms similar to cutaneous anthrax, with the exception of black areas, and may also cause infection deep into the muscle and spread faster.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] This can make it harder to recognise and treat.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Inhalation anthrax usually develops within a week after exposure, but may take up to 2 months.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] During the first few days of illness, most people have fever, chills, and fatigue.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] These symptoms may be accompanied by cough, shortness of breath, chest pain, and nausea or vomiting, making inhalation anthrax difficult to distinguish from influenza and community-acquired pneumonia.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] This is often described as the prodromal period.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Over the next day or so, shortness of breath, cough, and chest pain become more common, and complaints not involving the chest such as nausea, vomiting, altered mental status, sweats, and headache develop in around one-third or more of people.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Upper respiratory tract symptoms occur in only a quarter of people, and muscle pains are rare.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Altered mental status or shortness of breath generally brings people to healthcare and marks the fulminant phase of illness.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] It infects the lymph nodes in the chest first, rather than the lungs themselves, a condition called hemorrhagic mediastinitis, causing bloody fluid to accumulate in the chest cavity, thereby causing shortness of breath.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The second (pneumonia) stage occurs when the infection spreads from the lymph nodes to the lungs.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Symptoms of the second stage develop suddenly within hours or days after the first stage.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Symptoms include high fever, extreme shortness of breath, shock, and rapid death within 48 hours in fatal cases.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Gastrointestinal (GI) infection is most often caused by consuming anthrax-infected meat and is characterized by diarrhea, potentially with blood, abdominal pains, acute inflammation of the intestinal tract, and loss of appetite.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Lesions have been found in the intestines and in the mouth and throat.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] After the bacterium invades the gastrointestinal system, it spreads to the bloodstream and throughout the body, while continuing to make toxins.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The production of two powerful exotoxins and lethal toxin by the bacteria causes death.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Veterinarians can often tell a possible anthrax-induced death by its sudden occurrence and the dark, nonclotting blood that oozes from the body orifices.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Most anthrax bacteria inside the body after death are outcompeted and destroyed by anaerobic bacteria within minutes to hours post mortem, but anthrax vegetative bacteria that escape the body via oozing blood or opening the carcass may form hardy spores.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] These vegetative bacteria are not contagious.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] One spore forms per vegetative bacterium.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The triggers for spore formation are not known, but oxygen tension and lack of nutrients may play roles.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Once formed, these spores are very hard to eradicate.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The infection of herbivores (and occasionally humans) by inhalation normally begins with inhaled spores being transported through the air passages into the tiny air sacs (alveoli) in the lungs.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The spores are then picked up by scavenger cells (macrophages) in the lungs and transported through small vessels (lymphatics) to the lymph nodes in the central chest cavity (mediastinum).
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Damage caused by the anthrax spores and bacilli to the central chest cavity can cause chest pain and difficulty breathing.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Once in the lymph nodes, the spores germinate into active bacilli that multiply and eventually burst the macrophages, releasing many more bacilli into the bloodstream to be transferred to the entire body.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Once in the bloodstream, these bacilli release three proteins: lethal factor, edema factor, and protective antigen.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The three are not toxic by themselves, but their combination is incredibly lethal to humans.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Protective antigen combines with these other two factors to form lethal toxin and edema toxin, respectively.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] These toxins are the primary agents of tissue destruction, bleeding, and death of the host.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] If antibiotics are administered too late, even if the antibiotics eradicate the bacteria, some hosts still die of toxemia because the toxins produced by the bacilli remain in their systems at lethal dose levels.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax can enter the human body through the intestines (gastrointestinal), lungs (pulmonary), or skin (cutaneous), and causes distinct clinical symptoms based on its site of entry.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax does not usually spread from an infected human to an uninfected human.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] If the disease is fatal to the person's body, its mass of anthrax bacilli becomes a potential source of infection to others and special precautions should be used to prevent further contamination.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Pulmonary anthrax, if left untreated, is almost always fatal.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Historically, pulmonary anthrax was called woolsorters' disease because it was an occupational hazard for people who sorted wool.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Today, this form of infection is extremely rare in industrialized nations.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Cutaneous anthrax is the most common form of transmission but also the least dangerous of the three transmissions.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Gastrointestinal anthrax is likely fatal if left untreated, but very rare.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The spores of anthrax are able to survive in harsh conditions for decades or even centuries.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Such spores can be found on all continents, including Antarctica.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Disturbed grave sites of infected animals have been known to cause infection after 70 years.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In one such event, a young boy died from gastrointestinal anthrax due to the thawing of reindeer corpses from 75 years before contact.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax spores traveled through groundwater used for drinking and caused tens of people to be hospitalized, largely children.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Occupational exposure to infected animals or their products (such as skin, wool, and meat) is the usual pathway of exposure for humans.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Workers exposed to dead animals and animal products are at the highest risk, especially in countries where anthrax is more common.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax in livestock grazing on open range where they mix with wild animals still occasionally occurs in the U.S. and elsewhere.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In the US, metal working has been noted as a risk factor for a disease closely resembling anthrax.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Many workers who deal with wool and animal hides are routinely exposed to low levels of anthrax spores, but most exposure levels are not sufficient to produce infection.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] A lethal infection is reported to result from inhalation of about 10,000–20,000 spores, though this dose varies among host species.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] PA plus LF produces lethal toxin, and PA plus EF produces edema toxin.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] These toxins cause death and tissue swelling (edema), respectively.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] To enter the cells, the edema and lethal factors use another protein produced by *B. anthracis* called protective antigen, which binds to two surface receptors on the host cell.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] A cell protease then cleaves PA into two fragments: PA20 and PA63.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] PA20 dissociates into the extracellular medium, playing no further role in the toxic cycle.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] PA63 then oligomerizes with six other PA63 fragments forming a heptameric ring-shaped structure named a prepore.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Once in this shape, the complex can competitively bind up to three EFs or LFs, forming a resistant complex.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Receptor-mediated endocytosis occurs next, providing the newly formed toxic complex access to the interior of the host cell.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The acidified environment within the endosome triggers the heptamer to release the LF and/or EF into the cytosol.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] It is unknown how exactly the complex results in the death of the cell.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Edema factor is a calmodulin-dependent adenylate cyclase.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Adenylate cyclase catalyzes the conversion of ATP into cyclic AMP (cAMP) and pyrophosphate.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The complexation of adenylate cyclase with calmodulin removes calmodulin from stimulating calcium-triggered signaling, thus inhibiting the immune response.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] To be specific, LF inactivates neutrophils (a type of phagocytic cell) by the process just described so they cannot phagocytose bacteria.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Throughout history, lethal factor was presumed to cause macrophages to make TNF and interleukin 1 beta (IL1β).
[src:anthrax/anthrax] TNF is a cytokine whose primary role is to regulate immune cells, as well as to induce inflammation and apoptosis or programmed cell death.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Interleukin 1 beta is another cytokine that also regulates inflammation and apoptosis.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The overproduction of TNF and IL1β ultimately leads to septic shock and death.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Various techniques may be used for the direct identification of *B. anthracis* in clinical material.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] *Bacillus* spp. are quite large in size (3 to 4 μm long), they may grow in long chains, and they stain Gram-positive.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] To confirm the organism is *B. anthracis*, rapid diagnostic techniques such as polymerase chain reaction-based assays and immunofluorescence microscopy may be used.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] All *Bacillus* species grow well on 5% sheep blood agar and other routine culture media.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Polymyxin-lysozyme-EDTA-thallous acetate can be used to isolate *B. anthracis* from contaminated specimens, and bicarbonate agar is used as an identification method to induce capsule formation.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] *Bacillus* spp. usually grow within 24 hours of incubation at 35 °C, in ambient air (room temperature) or in 5% CO2.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] If bicarbonate agar is used for identification, then the medium must be incubated in 5% CO2.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] *B. anthracis* colonies are medium-large, gray, flat, and irregular with swirling projections, often referred to as having a "medusa head" appearance, and are not hemolytic on 5% sheep blood agar.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The bacteria are not motile, susceptible to penicillin, and produce a wide zone of lecithinase on egg yolk agar.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Confirmatory testing to identify *B. anthracis* includes gamma bacteriophage testing, indirect hemagglutination, and enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay to detect antibodies.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The best confirmatory precipitation test for anthrax is the Ascoli test.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Precautions are taken to avoid contact with the skin and any fluids exuded through natural body openings of a deceased body that is suspected of harboring anthrax.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The body should be put in strict quarantine.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] A blood sample is collected and sealed in a container and analyzed in an approved laboratory to ascertain if anthrax is the cause of death.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The body should be sealed in an airtight body bag and incinerated to prevent the transmission of anthrax spores.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Microscopic visualization of the encapsulated bacilli, usually in very large numbers, in a blood smear stained with polychrome methylene blue (McFadyean stain) is fully diagnostic, though the culture of the organism is still the gold standard for diagnosis.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Full isolation of the body is important to prevent possible contamination of others.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Protective, impermeable clothing and equipment such as rubber gloves, rubber apron, and rubber boots with no perforations are used when handling the body.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] No skin, especially if it has any wounds or scratches, should be exposed.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Disposable personal protective equipment is preferable, but if not available, decontamination can be achieved by autoclaving.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Used disposable equipment is burned and/or buried after use.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] All contaminated bedding or clothing is isolated in double plastic bags and treated as biohazard waste.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Respiratory equipment capable of filtering small particles, such the US National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health- and Mine Safety and Health Administration-approved high-efficiency respirator, is worn.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Addressing Anthrax from a One Health perspective reduces risks of transmission and better protects both human and animal populations.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Vaccines against anthrax for use in livestock and humans have had a prominent place in the history of medicine.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The French scientist Louis Pasteur developed the first effective veterinary vaccine in 1881.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Human anthrax vaccines were developed by the Soviet Union in the late 1930s and in the US and UK in the 1950s.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The current FDA-approved US vaccine was formulated in the 1960s.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Currently administered human anthrax vaccines include acellular subunit vaccine (United States) and live vaccine (Russia) varieties.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] All currently used anthrax vaccines show considerable local and general reactogenicity (erythema, induration, soreness, fever) and serious adverse reactions occur in about 1% of recipients.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The American product, BioThrax, is licensed by the FDA and was formerly administered in a six-dose primary series at 0, 2, 4 weeks and 6, 12, 18 months, with annual boosters to maintain immunity.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In 2008, the FDA approved omitting the week-2 dose, resulting in the currently recommended five-dose series.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] This five-dose series is available to military personnel, scientists who work with anthrax and members of the public who do jobs which cause them to be at-risk.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] New second-generation vaccines currently being researched include recombinant live vaccines and recombinant subunit vaccines.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In the 20th century the use of a modern product (BioThrax) to protect American troops against the use of anthrax in biological warfare was controversial.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Preventive antibiotics are recommended in those who have been exposed.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Early detection of sources of anthrax infection can allow preventive measures to be taken.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In response to the anthrax attacks of October 2001, the United States Postal Service (USPS) installed biodetection systems (BDSs) in their large-scale mail processing facilities.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] BDS response plans were formulated by the USPS in conjunction with local responders including fire, police, hospitals, and public health.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Employees of these facilities have been educated about anthrax, response actions, and prophylactic medication.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Because of the time delay inherent in getting final verification that anthrax has been used, prophylactic antibiotic treatment of possibly exposed personnel must be started as soon as possible.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax cannot be spread from person to person, except in the rare case of skin exudates from cutaneous anthrax.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] However, a person's clothing and body may be contaminated with anthrax spores.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Effective decontamination of people can be accomplished by a thorough wash-down with antimicrobial soap and water.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Wastewater is treated with bleach or another antimicrobial agent.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Effective decontamination of articles can be accomplished by boiling them in water for 30 minutes or longer.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Chlorine bleach is ineffective in destroying spores and vegetative cells on surfaces, though formaldehyde is effective.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Burning clothing is very effective in destroying spores.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] After decontamination, there is no need to immunize, treat, or isolate contacts of persons ill with anthrax unless they were also exposed to the same source of infection.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Early antibiotic treatment of anthrax is essential; delay significantly lessens chances for survival.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Treatment for anthrax infection and other bacterial infections includes large doses of intravenous and oral antibiotics, such as fluoroquinolones (ciprofloxacin), doxycycline, erythromycin, vancomycin, or penicillin.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] FDA-approved agents include ciprofloxacin, doxycycline, and penicillin.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In possible cases of pulmonary anthrax, early antibiotic prophylaxis treatment is crucial to prevent possible death.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Many attempts have been made to develop new drugs against anthrax, but existing drugs are effective if treatment is started soon enough.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In May 2009, Human Genome Sciences submitted a biologic license application (BLA, permission to market) for its new drug, raxibacumab (brand name ABthrax) intended for emergency treatment of inhaled anthrax.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] On 14 December 2012, the US Food and Drug Administration approved raxibacumab injection to treat inhalational anthrax.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Raxibacumab is a monoclonal antibody that neutralizes toxins produced by *B. anthracis*.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In March 2016, FDA approved a second anthrax treatment using a monoclonal antibody which neutralizes the toxins produced by *B. anthracis*.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Obiltoxaximab is approved to treat inhalational anthrax in conjunction with appropriate antibacterial drugs, and for prevention when alternative therapies are not available or appropriate.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In 2015, anthrax immune globulin was approved by the FDA.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] It is a human immune globulin produced from the plasma of anthrax-vaccinated individuals.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Its mechanism is distinct from monoclonal antibody treatments for anthrax, which inactivate the anthrax toxin.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] An immunizing agent, it increases the natural immune response against anthrax *in vivo*.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Serious side effects include thrombosis, hemolysis, asceptic menengitis, TRALI, and anaphylaxis.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Treatment of multi-drug resistant, antibody- or vaccine-resistant Anthrax is also possible.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Legler, et al. showed that pegylated CapD (capsule depolymerase) could provide protection against 5 LD50 exposures to lethal Ames spores without the use of antibiotics, monoclonal antibodies, or vaccines.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The CapD enzyme removes the poly-D-glutamate (PDGA) capsular material from the bacteria, rendering it susceptible to the innate immune responses.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The unencapsulated bacteria can then be cleared.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Cutaneous anthrax is rarely fatal if treated, because the infection area is limited to the skin, preventing the lethal factor, edema factor, and protective antigen from entering and destroying a vital organ.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Without treatment, up to 20% of cutaneous skin infection cases progress to toxemia and death.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Before 2001, fatality rates for inhalation anthrax were 90%; since then, they have fallen to 45%.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] People that progress to the fulminant phase of inhalational anthrax nearly always die, with one case study showing a death rate of 97%.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax meningoencephalitis is also nearly always fatal.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Gastrointestinal anthrax infections can be treated, but usually result in fatality rates of 25% to 60%, depending upon how soon treatment commences.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Injection anthrax is the rarest form of anthrax, and has only been seen to have occurred in a group of heroin injecting drug users.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Globally, at least 2,000 cases occur a year.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In July 2022, dozens of cattle in a nature park in Lonjsko Polje, a flood plain by the Sava river, died of anthrax and 6 people have been hospitalized with light, skin-related symptoms.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In November 2008, a drum maker in the United Kingdom who worked with untreated animal skins contracted and died from anthrax.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In December 2009, an outbreak of anthrax occurred among heroin addicts in the Glasgow and Stirling areas of Scotland, resulting in 14 deaths.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The last fatal case of natural inhalational anthrax in the United States occurred in California in 1976, when a home weaver died after working with infected wool imported from Pakistan.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] To minimize the chance of spreading the disease, the body was transported to UCLA in a sealed plastic body bag within a sealed metal container for autopsy.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Gastrointestinal anthrax is exceedingly rare in the United States, with only two cases on record.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The first case was reported in 1942, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] During December 2009, the New Hampshire Department of Health and Human Services confirmed a case of gastrointestinal anthrax in an adult female.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The CDC investigated the source and the possibility that it was contracted from an African drum recently used by the woman taking part in a drum circle.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The woman apparently inhaled anthrax, in spore form, from the hide of the drum.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] She became critically ill, but with gastrointestinal anthrax rather than inhaled anthrax, which made her unique in American medical history.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The building where the infection took place was cleaned and reopened to the public and the woman recovered.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The New Hampshire state epidemiologist, Jodie Dionne-Odom, stated "It is a mystery.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In 2007 two cases of cutaneous anthrax were reported in Danbury, Connecticut.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The case involved a maker of traditional African-style drums who was working with a goat hide purchased from a dealer in New York City which had been previously cleared by Customs.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] While the hide was being scraped, a spider bite led to the spores entering the bloodstream.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Several cases that have occurred since 1997 involve metalworkers, especially welders, leading to a 2022 study coining the term "Welder's Anthrax".
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The exact relationship between metalworking and anthrax is unknown, though the 2022 study by CDC researchers speculates that metal fumes from welding may have an immunosuppressive effect.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthracis* and *B. cereus* need iron to survive, and that welders may accrue excess iron in their lungs.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Robert Koch, a German physician and scientist, first identified the bacterium that caused the anthrax disease in 1875 in Wollstein (now Wolsztyn, Poland).
[src:anthrax/anthrax] His pioneering work in the late 19th century was one of the first demonstrations that diseases could be caused by microbes.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In a groundbreaking series of experiments, he uncovered the lifecycle and means of transmission of anthrax.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] His experiments not only helped create an understanding of anthrax but also helped elucidate the role of microbes in causing illness at a time when debates still took place over spontaneous generation versus cell theory.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Koch went on to study the mechanisms of other diseases and won the 1905 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his discovery of the bacterium causing tuberculosis.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Although Koch arguably made the greatest theoretical contribution to understanding anthrax, other researchers were more concerned with the practical questions of how to prevent the disease.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In Britain, where anthrax affected workers in the wool, worsted, hides, and tanning industries, it was viewed with fear.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] John Henry Bell, a doctor born & based in Bradford, first made the link between the mysterious and deadly "woolsorter's disease" and anthrax, showing in 1878 that they were one and the same.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In the early 20th century, Friederich Wilhelm Eurich, the German bacteriologist who settled in Bradford with his family as a child, carried out important research for the local Anthrax Investigation Board.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Eurich also made valuable contributions to a Home Office Departmental Committee of Inquiry, established in 1913 to address the continuing problem of industrial anthrax.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] His work in this capacity, much of it collaboration with the factory inspector G.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Elmhirst Duckering, led directly to the Anthrax Prevention Act (1919).
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax posed a major economic challenge in France and elsewhere during the 19th century.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Horses, cattle, and sheep were particularly vulnerable, and national funds were set aside to investigate the production of a vaccine.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] French scientist Louis Pasteur was charged with the production of a vaccine, following his successful work in developing methods that helped to protect the important wine and silk industries.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In May 1881, Pasteur – in collaboration with his assistants Jean-Joseph Henri Toussaint, Émile Roux and others – performed a public experiment at Pouilly-le-Fort to demonstrate his concept of vaccination.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] He prepared two groups of 25 sheep, one goat, and several cattle.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The animals of one group were twice injected with an anthrax vaccine prepared by Pasteur, at an interval of 15 days; the control group was left unvaccinated.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Thirty days after the first injection, both groups were injected with a culture of live anthrax bacteria.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] All the animals in the unvaccinated group died, while all of the animals in the vaccinated group survived.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] After this apparent triumph, which was widely reported in the local, national, and international press, Pasteur made strenuous efforts to export the vaccine beyond France.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] He used his celebrity status to establish Pasteur Institutes across Europe and Asia, and his nephew, Adrien Loir, travelled to Australia in 1888 to try to introduce the vaccine to combat anthrax in New South Wales.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Ultimately, the vaccine was unsuccessful in the challenging climate of rural Australia, and it was soon superseded by a more robust version developed by local researchers John Gunn and John McGarvie Smith.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The human vaccine for anthrax became available in 1954.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] This was a cell-free vaccine instead of the live-cell Pasteur-style vaccine used for veterinary purposes.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] An improved cell-free vaccine became available in 1970.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax spores can survive for very long periods of time in the environment after release.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Nonoxidizing agents shown to be effective for anthrax decontamination include methyl bromide, formaldehyde, and metam sodium.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] All of the aforementioned anthrax decontamination technologies have been demonstrated to be effective in laboratory tests conducted by the US EPA or others.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Decontamination techniques for *Bacillus anthracis* spores are affected by the material with which the spores are associated, environmental factors such as temperature and humidity, and microbiological factors such as the spore species, anthracis strain, and test methods used.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] A bleach solution for treating hard surfaces has been approved by the EPA.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Chlorine dioxide has emerged as the preferred biocide against anthrax-contaminated sites, having been employed in the treatment of numerous government buildings over the past decade.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Its chief drawback is the need for *in situ* processes to have the reactant on demand.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] To speed the process, trace amounts of a nontoxic catalyst composed of iron and tetroamido macrocyclic ligands are combined with sodium carbonate and bicarbonate and converted into a spray.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The spray formula is applied to an infested area and is followed by another spray containing tert-butyl hydroperoxide.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Using the catalyst method, complete destruction of all anthrax spores can be achieved in under 30 minutes.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] A standard catalyst-free spray destroys fewer than half the spores in the same amount of time.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Cleanups at a Senate Office Building, several contaminated postal facilities, and other US government and private office buildings, a collaborative effort headed by the Environmental Protection Agency showed decontamination to be possible, but time-consuming and costly.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Clearing the Senate Office Building of anthrax spores cost $27 million, according to the Government Accountability Office.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Cleaning the Brentwood postal facility in Washington cost $130 million and took 26 months.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Since then, newer and less costly methods have been developed.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Cleanup of anthrax-contaminated areas on ranches and in the wild is much more problematic.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Carcasses may be burned, though often 3 days are needed to burn a large carcass and this is not feasible in areas with little wood.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Carcasses may also be buried, though the burying of large animals deeply enough to prevent resurfacing of spores requires much manpower and expensive tools.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Carcasses have been soaked in formaldehyde to kill spores, though this has environmental contamination issues.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Block burning of vegetation in large areas enclosing an anthrax outbreak has been tried; this, while environmentally destructive, causes healthy animals to move away from an area with carcasses in search of fresh grass.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Some wildlife workers have experimented with covering fresh anthrax carcasses with shadecloth and heavy objects.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] This prevents some scavengers from opening the carcasses, thus allowing the putrefactive bacteria within the carcass to kill the vegetative *B. anthracis* cells and preventing sporulation.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] This method also has drawbacks, as scavengers such as hyenas are capable of infiltrating almost any exclosure.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The experimental site at Gruinard Island is said to have been decontaminated with a mixture of formaldehyde and seawater by the Ministry of Defence.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] It is not clear whether similar treatments had been applied to US test sites.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax spores have been used as a biological warfare weapon.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Its first modern incidence occurred when Nordic rebels, supplied by the German General Staff, used anthrax with unknown results against the Imperial Russian Army in Finland in 1916.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax was first tested as a biological warfare agent by Unit 731 of the Japanese Kwantung Army in Manchuria during the 1930s; some of this testing involved intentional infection of prisoners of war, thousands of whom died.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax, designated at the time as Agent N, was also investigated by the Allies in the 1940s.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The pellets would be eaten by cattle, which would in turn be eaten by the human population and as such severely disrupt the German war effort.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In the same year, bioweapons tests were carried out on the uninhabited Gruinard Island in the Scottish Highlands, with Porton Down scientists studying the effect of anthrax on the island's population of sheep.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Ultimately, five million pellets were created, though plans to drop them over Germany using Royal Air Force bombers in 1944 were scrapped after the success of Operation Overlord and the subsequent Allied liberation of France.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] All pellets were destroyed using incinerators in 1945.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Weaponized anthrax was part of the US stockpile prior to 1972, when the United States signed the Biological Weapons Convention.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] President Nixon ordered the dismantling of US biowarfare programs in 1969 and the destruction of all existing stockpiles of bioweapons.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In 1978–79, the Rhodesian government used anthrax against cattle and humans during its campaign against rebels.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The Soviet Union created and stored 100 to 200 tons of anthrax spores at Kantubek on Vozrozhdeniya Island; they were abandoned in 1992 and destroyed in 2002.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] American military and British Army personnel are no longer routinely vaccinated against anthrax prior to active service in places where biological attacks are considered a threat.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Despite signing the 1972 agreement to end bioweapon production, the government of the Soviet Union had an active bioweapons program that included the production of hundreds of tons of anthrax after this period.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] On 2 April 1979, some of the over one million people living in Sverdlovsk (now called Ekaterinburg, Russia), about 1,370 kilometres (850 mi) east of Moscow, were exposed to an accidental release of anthrax from a biological weapons complex located near there.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] At least 94 people were infected, of whom at least 68 died.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] One victim died four days after the release, 10 over an eight-day period at the peak of the deaths, and the last six weeks later.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Extensive cleanup, vaccinations, and medical interventions managed to save about 30 of the victims.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Extensive cover-ups and destruction of records by the KGB continued from 1979 until Russian president Boris Yeltsin admitted this anthrax accident in 1992.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Jeanne Guillemin reported in 1999 that a combined Russian and United States team investigated the accident in 1992.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Nearly all of the night-shift workers of a ceramics plant directly across the street from the biological facility (compound 19) became infected, and most died.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Since most were men, some NATO governments suspected the Soviet Union had developed a sex-specific weapon.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The government blamed the outbreak on the consumption of anthrax-tainted meat, and ordered the confiscation of all uninspected meat that entered the city.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] They also ordered all stray dogs to be shot and people not have contact with sick animals.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Also, a voluntary evacuation and anthrax vaccination program was established for people from 18 to 55.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] To support the cover-up story, Soviet medical and legal journals published articles about an outbreak in livestock that caused gastrointestinal anthrax in people having consumed infected meat, and cutaneous anthrax in people having come into contact with the animals.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] All medical and public health records were confiscated by the KGB.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In addition to the medical problems the outbreak caused, it also prompted Western countries to be more suspicious of a covert Soviet bioweapons program and to increase their surveillance of suspected sites.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In 1986, the US government was allowed to investigate the incident, and concluded the exposure was from aerosol anthrax from a military weapons facility.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In 1992, President Yeltsin admitted he was "absolutely certain" that "rumors" about the Soviet Union violating the 1972 Bioweapons Treaty were true.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The Soviet Union, like the US and UK, had agreed to submit information to the UN about their bioweapons programs, but omitted known facilities and never acknowledged their weapons program.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In theory, anthrax spores can be cultivated with minimal special equipment and a first-year collegiate microbiological education.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] To make large amounts of an aerosol form of anthrax suitable for biological warfare requires extensive practical knowledge, training, and highly advanced equipment.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Concentrated anthrax spores were used for bioterrorism in the 2001 anthrax attacks in the United States, delivered by mailing postal letters containing the spores.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The letters were sent to several news media offices and two Democratic senators: Tom Daschle of South Dakota and Patrick Leahy of Vermont.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] As a result, 22 were infected and five died.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Only a few grams of material were used in these attacks and in August 2008, the US Department of Justice announced they believed that Bruce Ivins, a senior biodefense researcher employed by the United States government, was responsible.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] These events also spawned many anthrax hoaxes.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Due to these events, the US Postal Service installed biohazard detection systems at its major distribution centers to actively scan for anthrax being transported through the mail.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] As of 2020, no positive alerts by these systems have occurred.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In response to the postal anthrax attacks and hoaxes, the United States Postal Service sterilized some mail using gamma irradiation and treatment with a proprietary enzyme formula supplied by Sipco Industries.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] A scientific experiment performed by a high school student, later published in the *Journal of Medical Toxicology*, suggested a domestic electric iron at its hottest setting (at least 400 °F (204 °C)) used for at least 5 minutes should destroy all anthrax spores in a common postal envelope.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax primarily affects herbivores such as cattle, sheep, and goats, but a wide range of mammals, birds, and even humans can also be susceptible.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Infection typically occurs through the ingestion of spores in contaminated soil or plants.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Once inside the host, the spores transform into active bacteria, producing lethal toxins that lead to severe symptoms.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Infected animals often exhibit high fever, rapid breathing, and convulsions, and they may succumb to the disease within hours to days.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] The presence of anthrax can pose significant challenges to livestock management and wildlife conservation efforts, making it a critical concern for both animal health and public health, as it can occasionally be transmitted to humans through contact with infected animals or contaminated products.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Infected animals may stagger, have difficulty breathing, tremble, and finally collapse and die within a few hours.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax is especially rare in dogs and cats, as is evidenced by a single reported case in the United States in 2001.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Anthrax outbreaks occur in some wild animal populations with some regularity.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] Russian researchers estimate arctic permafrost contains around 1.5 million anthrax-infected reindeer carcasses, and the spores may survive in the permafrost for 105 years.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] A risk exists that global warming in the Arctic can thaw the permafrost, releasing anthrax spores in the carcasses.
[src:anthrax/anthrax] In 2016, an anthrax outbreak in reindeer was linked to a 75-year-old carcass that defrosted during a heat wave.
